{This lecture examines the most important positional patterns that every Italian player should know. These concepts can be applied in almost all lines of the Italian Game. The lecture is divided into the following parts: 1) Isolated Italian Bishop 2) Fundamental Mistakes in 1.e4 e5 positions 3) Be7 or Kingside Fianchetto? 4) Symmetrical Endgames arising after dxe5}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Isolated Italian bishop"]
[Black "knight - Example 1"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp1bppp/2np1n2/4p3/2BPP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "77"]
[WhiteTeam "Germany"]
[BlackTeam "Germany"]
[WhiteTeamCountry "GER"]
[BlackTeamCountry "GER"]

{White's play in the centre has been premature. By forcing his opponent to release the tension immediately, Black can comfortably equalise.} 1... Bg4 $1 2. dxe5 (2. d5 $6 Nd4 3. Be2 Nxe2+ 4. Qxe2 c6 $15) 2... dxe5 $1 (2... Nxe5 {As a general rule, this recapture is correct with a bishop on g7, but not with a bishop on c5 or e7.} 3. Be2 Nxf3+ 4. Bxf3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Re8 6. Bf4 $14) (2... Bxf3 3. Qxf3 Nxe5 4. Qe2 Nxc4 5. Qxc4 Re8 6. Bf4 c6 7. Rad1 $14) 3. Qxd8 $2 {Despite the symmetrical pawns, there is nothing drawish about this endgame. White's only active unit is the Italian bishop, and the following moves will show why this bishop needs to be supported by its colleagues in order to be a good piece.} Raxd8 4. Be3 Bxf3 5. gxf3 Nd4 6. Bxd4 Rxd4 $17 {The opposite-coloured bishops are only a superficial and temporary feature of this position. In the long run, White can hardly avoid the exchange of his knight for Black's bishop.} 7. Bb3 c6 8. Rad1 Rfd8 9. Rxd4 Rxd4 10. Rd1 Rxd1+ 11. Nxd1 Bc5 12. Ne3 ({White cannot avoid trading the knight, for example} 12. c4 Bd4) 12... Bxe3 13. fxe3 {With a healthy pawn structure (for example e3-pawn on g2), Black would only have a small advantage. Here however, White's structural deficits and the fact that his bishop has no active prospects at all make his position strategically losing.} Kf8 14. c3 Ke7 15. Kf2 Ne8 16. Bc2 Nd6 {The ideal square for the knight at this moment, eyeing the e4-pawn and the c4-square while supporting potential pawn breaks on both sides of the board.} 17. Bd3 b5 18. f4 $6 {This weakens e4 and makes it easier for Black to create a kingside passed pawn.} ({But passive defence doesn't save Black either, for example} 18. Ke2 Kd7 19. b4 Kc7 20. Kd2 Kb6 21. Ke2 a5 22. a3 c5 23. Kd2 Ne8 24. Ke2 Nc7 25. Kd2 Na6 26. bxc5+ (26. a4 $5 {is an interesting attempt to muddy the waters with a pawn sacrifice. White will gain a protected passed pawn which makes the conversion of Black's advantage far from trivial:} bxa4 27. b5 Nc7 28. c4 Ne6 29. Kc3 Nf8 30. Kb2 Ng6 31. Ka3 Nh4 32. Be2 Ng2 33. Kxa4 Nxe3 34. Kb3 Ng2 35. Kc3 Nf4 36. Bd1 Ne6 37. Kd3 h5 38. Kd2 h4 39. Ke3 g6 40. Kd3 f5 41. exf5 gxf5 42. Ke3 f4+ 43. Ke4 Ng5+ $1 44. Kxe5 Nxf3+ 45. Kxf4 Nd2 $19) 26... Nxc5 27. Bc2 g5 28. Bd1 Nb7 29. Bc2 Nd6 30. Bd3 a4 31. Kc2 Kc5 32. Kd2 Nc4+ 33. Bxc4 Kxc4 {And Black eventually wins by Zugzwang.}) 18... f6 19. Ke2 Kd7 ({Now and in most of the next moves, the immediate} 19... g5 {would have been more precise, creating a decisive passed pawn on the kingside.}) 20. b4 Kc7 21. Kd2 Kb6 22. Kc2 c5 23. a3 a5 {A standard plan in these endgames: Black mounts pressure on b4 to provoke bxa5 or bxc5, which will give the king access to the fifth rank and weaken White's structure.} 24. Kb2 Nf7 {Next part of the plan: The knight is routed to c6, after which White must release the tension.} 25. Bc2 Nd8 26. Bd3 Nc6 {The plan has successfully been implemented. White cannot further protect b4 and has to make another concession.} 27. bxc5+ Kxc5 28. Kc2 h6 29. Kb2 g5 30. fxg5 fxg5 {Black practically has an extra pawn. Now the knight transfer to f6 and the push of his kingside pawns decides the game.} 31. Be2 Ne7 32. Bf3 Ng8 33. h3 Nf6 34. Kc2 a4 35. Kd3 h5 36. Kc2 g4 37. hxg4 hxg4 38. Bg2 Ne8 39. Kd2 Nd6 0-1

