{With the dark-squared bishops exchanged, White has to treat central tensions very carefully. While closing the position now hardly makes sense positionally, trading into a symmetrical structure also leaves Black in the slightly preferable situation.} 11. dxe5 $6 Nxe5 $1 {Unfortunately, there is no general rule for Black to know how to recapture.} (11... dxe5 {is also playable, but swapping a pair of knights is desirable here for several reasons: - White cannot opt for a different structure, as 12.Be2? Ng4 would drop a pawn. - the c6-knight was standing in the way of Black's queenside pawns - any exchange that brings the game closer to a pure Italian bishop vs. knight position can generally be considered welcome}) 12. Nxe5 dxe5 $15 {Again, the Italian bishop, which looks so good on the a2-g8 diagonal, will end up as the worst piece on the board.} 13. Nd2 b5 {With the c6-knight gone, Black can quickly gain space on the queenside.} ({Less ambitious is} 13... Be6 $6 {, with a drawish position after} 14. Bxe6 Qxe6 $11) 14. Bb3 c5 15. Nf3 Bg4 16. Rfd1 c4 17. Bc2 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 g6 $17 {The exchange of rooks on the only open file can hardly be avoided. After this, Black's knight is clearly superior both in positions with queens left on the board and in pure minor piece endgames.} *

