{Another typical mistake is the premature pawn push in the centre. In many chess openings, and certainly in the Italian, it's a typical phenomenon that very eager and ambitious play in the centre gets punished - the pawns that were supposed to be strong come under attack and one is forced to play passively and make concessions in order to defend them.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. O-O a6 6. c3 d6 7. a4 h6 8. d4 $2 {Expanding in the centre with tempo due to hitting the c5-bishop, while Black's king is still in the centre. What could possibly go wrong?} Ba7 {Turns out, White's task to protect both d4 and e4 is not at all pleasant. Meanwhile, Black is threatening to increase the pressure with Bg4 and/or simply castle, play Re8 or Qe7 and ask questions about the e4-pawn.} 9. Re1 (9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {looks slightly preferable for Black due to his more active king. The greedy} 12. Bxf7 $2 {only leads to trouble after} Rf8 13. Bb3 Ng4 $17) 9... O-O 10. h3 {This prevents Bg4, but Black has the pleasant choice between the tactical solution} (10. Bb3 {This prevents ideas like Nxe4 and exd4 followed by d6-d5 but neglects Black's other threat:} Bg4 $17 {White has no good way to deal with the pressure against d4.}) 10... Nxe4 ({and the quiet} 10... Re8 $15) ({Also thematical would be} 10... exd4 11. cxd4 d5 {, but it turns out that after} 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Qxd5 14. Nc3 $14 {, followed by d4-d5, White is slightly better despite the loss of his bishop pair.}) *

