{A common theme from the Italian and the Spanish opening is that Black develops his king's bishop to e7 and later "corrects" the position by playing Re8, Bf8, g7-g6 and Bg7. Why is that not simply a waste of two tempi? The explanation is that in this type of position, g7 generally tends to be the best square for the bishop. If White expands in the centre, the bishop stands ready to defend e5 or become active on the long diagonal. If White doesn't, Black can usually think about playing one of the pawn breaks d6-d5 and f7-f5. Both work much better with a fianchetto than with a bishop on e7. So why don't we see an early g7-g6 more often? The reason is that it is somewhat slow and White can often embarass Black with energetic play. In the worst case it's a quick Ng5, attacking f7 twice, and Black is not yet ready to castle. More often though, White just strikes in the centre immediately with d2-d4 or d3-d4, trying to exploit the fact that Black needs two more moves to castle. The purpose of this small opening study is to show arguments for and against the fianchetto in a topical line of the Italian. However, as a player who responds to 1.e4 with 1...e5, you should make it a habit to think about the possibility of playing g7-g6 and Bg7 instead of the more usual Be7 or Bc5.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 (3... g6 $6 4. d4 $1 {Black is not in a good position to deal with this energetic strike in the centre.} exd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. O-O d6 8. Nc3 $16 {Black is somewhat cramped, has a damaged pawn structure, and as soon as his knight develops, Bg5 will be unpleasant.}) 4. d3 h6 $5 {A slow but necessary precaution to play the already slow g7-g6 later.} (4... g6 $2 5. Ng5 d5 6. exd5 Na5 7. Bb5+ c6 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Ba4 $16) 5. O-O d6 6. c3 {The most popular move in this position. White anticipates Black's intention to play a kingside fianchetto and prepares d3-d4 as a follow-up.} ({The slow} 6. a4 {is also played, when} g6 {can be considered mandatory.} ({White is not threatening anything for the moment, so there is no reason to opt for the "safer" bishop development} 6... Be7 $6)) {Now} 6... g6 {is clearly Black's main choice. White will respond with d3-d4, which will lead to a complicated position that is acceptable for both sides.} ({But} 6... Be7 $5 {is also played and fully reasonable: Black prevents d3-d4 for the moment and prepares a quick castling.}) *

