{The following game's opening is obviously not an Italian. However, after just a few moves, a typical Italian position will be reached.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 {As a general rule, with the bishop on g7, there is no reason to recapture with the pawn first. If White tries to maintain this structure, Black's pieces will be rather active, including said bishop.} 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qe2 Bh6 $1 $15 {As has been established in earlier examples, a feature of these symmetrical positions with an open d-file is that White would like to trade light-squared bishops and Black the dark-squared ones. Knowing this, the text move should not be too hard to find.} 11. Nc4 (11. Nf3 {can be answered with} Bxc1 12. Raxc1 Bg4 $1 13. Qe3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $15 {, and Black has already secured himself the favourable minor piece constellation of knight versus "Italian" bishop.}) 11... Bg4 12. f3 Bxc1 13. Raxc1 Be6 14. Qf2 Nd7 $2 {A remarkable strategic mistake from such a strong player.} (14... Bxc4 $1 15. Bxc4 Qe7 $15 {leads to the typical Black advantage of knight versus light-squared bishop.}) 15. Ne3 {Now White preserves his knight and the rest of the game is of no relevance for this lecture.} Nb6 16. Red1 Qg5 17. b3 Rad8 18. a4 a5 19. Qe1 Rd4 20. Nf1 Ra8 21. Qc3 Qe7 22. Be2 c5 23. Ne3 h5 24. Rb1 h4 25. Bc4 Nxc4 26. bxc4 Qg5 27. Re1 Rad8 28. Re2 h3 29. g3 f5 30. exf5 gxf5 31. Nf1 Qg7 32. Rbe1 e4 33. fxe4 f4 34. Qxa5 Bxc4 35. Rf2 Bxf1 36. Rexf1 fxg3 37. hxg3 Qxg3+ 38. Kh1 Rd1 0-1

