1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Be7 4. d4 d6 5. c3 Nf6 6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. Nxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8+ Bxd8 9. f3 O-O 10. Be3 Be7 11. Nd2 Rd8 12. Rd1 b6 13. Kf2 Bb7 14. Nb3 h6 15. g4 Ne8 16. Be2 Bh4+ 17. Kg2 a5 18. Nd2 Bc6 19. Nc4 {After both sides played the opening far from optimally, Black finds an interesting way to complicate this (so far) rather quiet and equal position.} Bb5 $5 20. Bf2 $2 {A strategical blunder. After resolving his short-term problems on the f1-a6 diagonal as quickly as possible, Black will find himself settled with a long-term problem: An endgame with an inferior minor piece.} Bxf2 21. Kxf2 Bxc4 {It's important to execute this exchange immediately.} ({After} 21... f6 22. Ne3 $14 {, White will be able to preserve his knight, which has good prospects to be activated via d5 or f5. It is not easy for Black to avoid the bishop exchange, as White's bishop looks rather active in this position and the remaining pieces are not going to leave the board in the next moves.}) 22. Bxc4 c6 $17 {Taking control of the d5-square is of course correct and the best move.} ({Still, if Black for some reason were down a tempo or forced to play} 22... Kf8 {, White achieves nothing with the pseudo-active} 23. Bd5 {This bishop would be strong in an opening or middlegame position, but in this endgame it just waits on d5 to be ejected, for example} Rab8 24. Rd2 Rd6 25. Rhd1 Rbd8 26. Ke3 Ke7 27. a4 Nf6 {Followed by R8d7 and c7-c6.}) 23. Be2 ({If White plays} 23. a4 {Black's next strategic goal is to provoke b2-b3, for example by transferring his knight to c5.} Kf8 24. b3 $2 {White shouldn't play this unless it's forced.} (24. Bd3 Nd6 25. Bc2 Nb7) 24... Nd6 25. Bd3 b5 26. axb5 (26. Be2 bxa4 27. bxa4 Nb7 $15 {Followed by Nc5.}) 26... cxb5 $15 {With the better chances for Black who has the pleasant choice between fixing the b3-pawn with b5-b4 and creating a distant passed pawn with a5-a4.}) 23... Kf8 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Rd1 Nd6 $1 {Breaking the general rule that rook and bishop are stronger than rook and knight, and therefore rooks should be exchanged. In this position, keeping a pair of rooks on the board increases Black's potential to play for a win. It's rather unlikely that his opponent's pieces will ever be able to cooperate very well.} (25... Ke7 26. Rxd8 Kxd8 $15 {was also possible, with reasonable chances in an objectively equal position.}) 26. a3 $6 Ke7 (26... a4 $1 {may have been better, fixing the structure immediately.}) 27. Ra1 (27. b4 $2 {would be White's standard defence in pure minor piece endings, but with the rooks on the board,} Ra8 {makes quite a difference. Now Black can open the a-file and penetrate with his rook anytime.}) 27... Nb7 ({Again, Black should have played} 27... a4 {, followed by Nb7-c5.}) 28. Rd1 Rxd1 {It would have been good and consistent for Black to keep the rooks on the board, as White has no entry squares on the d-file.} 29. Bxd1 Kd6 30. Ke3 Nc5 31. Bc2 a4 32. Bd1 b5 33. Kd2 Nb7 34. Be2 Kc5 35. Bd3 Nd6 36. Kc2 g6 37. Be2 f5 38. exf5 gxf5 39. h4 Kd5 40. Bd3 fxg4 41. fxg4 e4 42. Be2 Ke5 43. b3 Kf4 44. bxa4 bxa4 45. Kd2 Nb5 46. g5 hxg5 47. hxg5 Kxg5 48. Bd1 Nxa3 49. Bxa4 Nc4+ 50. Ke2 c5 51. Bb3 Nd6 52. Ke3 Kf5 53. Bg8 Ke5 54. Bb3 Nf5+ 55. Ke2 Kf4 56. Bc4 Ng3+ 57. Kd2 Kf3 58. Kc2 e3 59. Kd1 Kf2 60. Kc2 e2 61. Bxe2 Kxe2 0-1

