{[%evp 0,16,23,15,15,36,36,32,39,-33,-11,-43,-43,-101,-74,13,34,-25,8] The starting position of the Scotch Gambit arises after the moves:} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 {In this variation, Black is doing very well objectively if he knows what he is doing. After:} Nf6 {White has two main options After} 5. O-O {Papaioannou suggests} ({The other important direction is} 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 {Now, instead of the most common 6...Ne4, I suggest} Nd7 $1 {In his opinion, this move is more interesting if Black wants to play for a win. The arising positions are strategically complex and White can easily go wrong.}) 5... Nxe4 $1 {when the first critical position arises after} 6. Re1 d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 {At this point, Black has a choice. My suggestion is} Qd7 $1 {which is very reliable and easy to learn. He explains how Black can play for a win in the arising endgame positions.} *

