{[%evp 0,36,17,36,36,35,24,2,7,-43,-43,-24,-67,-32,40,31,25,13,-14,8,9,-54,-27,-14,0,0,0,-26,-39,1,1,1,16,13,16,21,6,-19,0]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. Bc4 Nf6 {This is my recommended move order. Black can also choose to play 4...Bc5 and it's very likely to transpose after the moves d2-d3 and Nf6 are included. Both move orders have positive and negative sides, but 4...Nf6 allows Black more flexibility since the bishop isn't committed to the c5-square yet.} 4. d4 exd4 {This transposes to the main line.}) 3... exd4 4. Bc4 {This is the starting position of the Scotch Gambit. In this variation, Black is doing very well objectively if he knows what he is doing.} Nf6 {White has two main moves in this position: 5.e5 and 5.0-0.} 5. e5 $1 (5. O-O $1 {This is an annoying system from White because it tends to be rather drawish, however, on the bright side, it's Black who has the better side of an equal position and can try to make something out of it.} Nxe4 $1 6. Re1 (6. Nc3 $2 {There are several Nc3 gambit ideas and none of them is working, but in any case, you need to know exactly how to reply with Black and you will reach a better position.} Nxc3 $1 (6... dxc3 {6...Nxc3 is a good and simple approach, while 6...dxc3 tends to be very complex.} 7. Bxf7+ $3 Kxf7 8. Qd5+ Ke8 9. Re1 $3 {This is far more dangerous and complicated than it seems.}) 7. bxc3 d5 $1 8. Bb5 Be7 $1 {Black will finish the development and stay with an extra pawn.} 9. Ne5 (9. Nxd4 Bd7 $17 10. Nxc6 bxc6 $17 (10... Bxc6 $17)) 9... Bd7 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 $1 11. cxd4 Bd7 (11... O-O $17) 12. Rb1 Bc8 $1 $17) (6. Nxd4 $2 d5 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Re1 Qf6 $1 9. Be3 O-O-O $17) 6... d5 7. Bxd5 $1 (7. Nc3 $2 dxc3 $1 {Usually Black would like to capture on c3 with the knight, but this time, the knight on e4 is pinned so Black must capture with the pawn.} 8. Bxd5 Be6 $1 9. Bxe4 (9. Rxe4 $2 Ne7 $1 $19) 9... Qxd1 10. Rxd1 cxb2 11. Bxb2 f6 $1 12. Nd4 (12. Rab1 Bxa2 $1 $17 (12... Rd8 $17)) 12... Nxd4 $1 {Although objectively this may be the best move, I prefer 12...Bd7 with the concept of doubling the pawns and having a safe king.} (12... Bd7 $1 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. Rab1 Bd6 $17) 13. Bxd4 O-O-O 14. Rab1 b6 $19) 7... Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qd7 $1 {Black also has alternatives from which the best is 8...Qh5, but 8... Qd7 is very good and it's easy to learn.} 9. Nxe4 (9. Rxe4+ $6 Be7 10. Nxd4 f5 $3 {This is the key move to remember! This gives Black a better position.} 11. Rf4 O-O $36 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Qd5+ Qxd5 14. Nxd5 Bd8 $1 $17) 9... Be7 10. Bg5 O-O $1 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 13. Nb3 {And now both 13...Rad8 and 13... Rae8 are good, from which I prefer 13...Rae8 when it will be very difficult for White to keep the balance and it's likely that White will get in a worse position since the bishop will be clearly stronger than the knight.} (13. Nb5 $6 Rad8 $1 $15 14. Nxc7 $4 Be6 $19) (13. Nc3 Qc5 14. Nb3 Qf5 15. Qd2 (15. Nd4 $6 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Bc6 17. Rac1 Rfd8 18. Qe3 h6 $15) 15... Rad8 $36) (13. Nxc6 Bxc6 $15) (13. Qd2 Rad8 $1 14. Nc3 Qb4 15. Nb3 Bf5 $15 16. Qe2 h6 17. Rad1 Rde8 18. Qxe8 Rxe8 19. Rxe8+ Kh7 $17) 13... Rad8 $1 (13... Rae8 $5 14. Qd2 (14. Nec5 Qxe1+ 15. Qxe1 Rxe1+ 16. Rxe1 Bc8 $15) 14... Bc8 15. Re3 Rd8 $132) 14. Nec5 Bc8 15. Rxe7 Rxd1+ 16. Rxd1 Nxe7 {0-1 (62) Alexakis,D-Schitco,I/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) (5. Ng5 $6 {This is a very bad move objectively which was used quite often by Paul Morphy, however, nowadays the computers show the way for Black. Be careful not to confuse 5.Ng5?! with 1.e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.Ng5 which is a playable system.} d5 $1 6. exd5 Qe7+ $3 7. Kf1 (7. Qe2 Qxe2+ 8. Kxe2 (8. Bxe2 Nxd5 $17) 8... Ne5 (8... Nb4 {This move is also possible.} 9. Na3 Nbxd5 $17) 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Kxd7 11. f4 Ng6 12. Nxf7 Re8+ 13. Kd1 Rg8 $17) 7... Ne5 8. Qxd4 Nxc4 9. Qxc4 h6 10. Nf3 Qc5 $1 11. Qxc5 Bxc5 12. c4 (12. Nc3 Bf5 $17) 12... Bf5 $17 13. Ke2 O-O-O 14. Be3 Rhe8 15. Nc3 Bxe3 16. fxe3 Ng4 17. Nd1 Bc2 $17) 5... d5 {This is the main move.} 6. Bb5 Nd7 $1 {This is a very interesting option for Black that is less popular than 6...Ne4!?, which is also a good move.} (6... Ne4 $5 {Sometimes Black chooses to play this move and there's nothing wrong with it, although sometimes it tends to lead to drawish positions.}) 7. O-O {This is the only decent move for White.} (7. Nxd4 $2 {Black gets a great position after this mistake from White.} Nxd4 8. Bxd7+ (8. Qxd4 c6 9. Be2 Bc5 {White will lose the e5-pawn soon.} 10. Qg4 (10. Qc3 Qe7 11. O-O O-O 12. Bf4 f6 $17) 10... g6 $17 11. Qg3 (11. e6 Nf6 12. exf7+ Kxf7 13. Qh4 Re8 14. Bg5 h6 $19) 11... O-O 12. f4 Qe7 13. Nc3 f6 $19) 8... Bxd7 (8... Qxd7 $5 {This is an interesting move on which it's important to note that Black can put the queen in front of the bishop in two scenarios - when White is missing the light-squared bishop because then Black can try to activate the queen on the light squares, or when White's light-squared bishop has already committed on the queenside and is stuck there.}) 9. Qxd4 Bf5 10. O-O Be7 (10... Bxc2 11. Nc3 c6 $17) 11. c3 O-O $17) (7. Bxc6 $2 {It is important to note that many players are often confusing the 7.Bxc6? with 7.0-0!-Be7 8.Bxc6! move order that is playable where Black continues with 8...Nb8 instead of capturing the pawn on e5. After 7.Bxc6?, Black can win a pawn.} bxc6 8. Nxd4 (8. Qxd4 Nc5 $17 (8... Bc5 $17) 9. O-O Ne6 10. Qa4 Bd7 $17 (10... Qd7 $17)) 8... Nxe5 $1 $15 9. O-O (9. Qe2 Qe7 10. O-O c5 11. Nb5 (11. Nb3 Nc4 $17) 11... c6 $17) 9... Qf6 $1 10. Re1 Be7 $17 11. h4 (11. f4 Ng6 $19) 11... Ng4 $1 (11... h6 $5 12. Qe2 Ng6 13. h5 Qxd4 14. hxg6 Qf6 15. gxf7+ (15. Bd2 $1 $11) 15... Kxf7 $17) 12. f3 Qxh4 13. fxg4 Bxg4 $15) 7... Be7 8. Bxc6 $1 {White should regain the pawn now.} (8. c3 $6 dxc3 9. Nxc3 Nb6 10. Nd4 Bd7 $15) (8. Re1 $6 O-O 9. Bxc6 (9. e6 fxe6 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxd4 Bc5 $19 (11... Nb8 $17)) 9... bxc6 10. Nxd4 Nb8 11. f4 (11. Qf3 $5 c5 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. Qxf5 Nc6 $1 (13... Qd7 14. Qxd7 Nxd7 15. Nc3 c6 16. b3 Rfe8 $11 {1-0 (47) Mamedov,R-Postny,E/St Petersburg RUS 2018}) 14. c3 (14. c4 dxc4 $1 15. Nc3 Nd4 16. Qe4 Rb8 17. Rb1 Qd7 $17) 14... Qc8 {Black already has a comfortable advantage.} 15. Qc2 (15. Qxc8 Rfxc8 16. Nd2 a5 $15) 15... Qe6 $1 16. f4 (16. Nd2 f6 $17) (16. Bf4 f6 $17) 16... g6 $1 $17 (16... d4 $5 17. f5 Qd5 18. c4 Qd7 $15)) (11. c4 c5 12. Nb5 c6 13. N5c3 Be6 14. Nd2 Nd7 $15 {1/2 (69)-1/2 Mamedov,R-Kevlishvili,R/Skopje 2018/Mega2019 Update}) (11. Nc3 c5 12. Nf3 (12. Nde2 d4 13. Ne4 Nc6 14. Bf4 Bf5 15. N2g3 Bg6 16. Qf3 Qd7 $15 {1-0 (59) Vajda, L-Sokolov,I/Porto Carras 2011/CBM 146}) 12... Be6 $15 {1/2 (88)-1/2 Najer,E-Predke,A/Batumi 2018/CBM 184} (12... c6 $15)) 11... c5 12. Nf3 Nc6 13. Nc3 (13. c4 dxc4 $1 14. Nc3 Be6 $17 (14... Bf5 {Is also possible.}) (14... Nd4 $17)) 13... Be6 (13... d4 14. Ne4 a5 $15) 14. f5 Bxf5 15. Nxd5 Nb4 $15) (8. e6 $2 fxe6 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxd4 {At first look, this looks good for White, however, White is two pawns down and still underdeveloped, so Black is close to winning!} Nb8 $1 11. Re1 (11. Qh5+ g6 12. Qh6 Bf8 13. Qe3 Qf6 $17) 11... O-O 12. Nxe6 Bxe6 13. Rxe6 Bc5 $1 14. Re2 (14. Be3 d4 $17) 14... Nd7 $17) 8... bxc6 9. Nxd4 Nb8 $3 {This is a typical idea for Black that's played quite often in this variation! With this move, Black covers both the c6-pawn and the f5-square. White needs to be very precise now since if White chooses a natural move like f4 or Be3 for example, White can easily land in a worse position.} 10. c4 $1 {This is the only move that causes problems for Black. If White opts for another move, Black would be at least equal.} (10. f4 $6 c5 11. Ne2 Nc6 12. Nbc3 (12. Nd2 O-O 13. Nf3 a5 $1 (13... f6 $15) 14. Ng3 f5 $15) 12... d4 13. Ne4 h5 $6 $15 14. Kh1 h4 15. h3 Bf5 $17) (10. Be3 $6 O-O $15 {1-0 (60) Chiburdanidze,M-Hund,B/Thessaloniki 1988/EXT 1997/[,Giannis]}) (10. Nc3 $5 O-O 11. Qf3 (11. f4 $2 c5 12. Nb3 (12. Nf3 d4 13. Ne4 Nc6 14. b3 a5 $15) 12... c6 13. f5 Re8 14. f6 gxf6 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Qf3 Nd7 17. Bh6 c4 18. Nd2 Kh8 $17) 11... Qd7 $1 (11... c5 $2 12. Nxd5 $18) (11... a5 $1 12. Bf4 Ra6 $1 $132) 12. h3 (12. Bf4 Qg4 $36) 12... Re8 $1 13. Bf4 Na6 14. Rfe1 Rb8 (14... Nc5 15. Rad1 Bf8 16. b3 Ne6 {Rerouting the knight with Na6-Nc5-Ne6 is a common plan in this line.}) 15. b3 Bb7 $132) 10... O-O $1 {The simplest move for Black.} (10... dxc4 $1 {This is a good move, however, Black needs to be precise afterward.} 11. Be3 O-O 12. Nc3 c5 13. Ndb5 Nc6 14. Qf3 Bd7 $1 (14... Bb7 $2 15. Rad1 Qc8 16. Qg3 $16 {0-1 (34) Principatibus-MenteOne/https://lichess.org/ JaBkaWXB 2020/}) 15. Qg3 (15. Rad1 a6 16. Na3 Nxe5 17. Qe4 Bd6 18. Nxc4 (18. Bxc5 Bc6 $19) 18... Nxc4 19. Qxc4 Be6 $17) (15. Nd5 $2 Nxe5 $19) 15... Kh8 16. Nd5 Rb8 17. Nbc3 (17. Nbxc7 Nd4 18. Bxd4 cxd4 $17) 17... Nd4 $17) 11. Qf3 (11. Nc3 c5 12. Ndb5 (12. Nb3 dxc4 13. Nd2 Nc6 $15 {0-1 (44) Rostami,H-Ponkratov,P/lichess.org INT 2020}) 12... d4 13. Nd5 c6 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. Qf3 cxb5 16. Qxa8 Bb7 17. Qxa7 bxc4 $13) (11. Nd2 $2 c5 12. N4f3 c6 $17 {½- (50) ½ Shehzad,S-Seo,J/Kragero NOR 2020}) 11... f6 $5 (11... c5 {This is a possible alternative for Black.} 12. Nb5 Ba6 $132) 12. e6 Bc5 13. Rd1 Bxd4 14. Rxd4 Bxe6 15. Nc3 Nd7 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Nxd5 c5 18. Rd1 Ne5 $132 *

