1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Nd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Re1 {This move is already an inaccuracy. White should have captured on c6 instead.} O-O 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxd4 Nb8 {Black is already better in this position thanks to White's inaccuracy on move 8.} 11. f4 (11. Bf4 c5 12. Nb5 a6 13. N5c3 Be6 14. Nd2 Nd7 {Developing the knight to c6 was also possible.} 15. Nf3 Nb6 16. Qc1 c6 17. Bg5 a5 {This is a very good strategical concept, strengthening the control over the dark squares.} 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 $15) (11. c3 c5 12. Ne2 Nc6 (12... f5 $2 {It's good to note that Black shouldn't play f5 when White's pawn isn't on f4 yet since it allows White access to the f4-square on which the knight can jump to.}) 13. f4 f5 14. Nd2 Be6 15. Nf3 Qd7 {This move is possible because of the following idea:} (15... h6 {Preventing Ng5 and preserving the bishop pair is a good idea.}) 16. Ng5 Nd8 {Black is rerouting the knight to the e6-square.} (16... Bxg5 $6 {After White recaptures with:} 17. fxg5 {the f4-square is now available as an outpost for the White knight.} d4 {The positions remains playable since Black also has counterplay.}) 17. Nxe6 Nxe6 $15 {The knight is the best blockading piece and now Black has a very comfortable position.}) 11... c5 12. Ne2 Nc6 (12... f6 {This is a good move that aims to open up the position since White can't play e5-e6.}) (12... f5 $17 {This is another playable move that leads to a good version for Black from this pawn structure.} 13. c3 Be6 {It's important to note that Black doesn't want the bishop from e6 to be under attack, so the White knights shouldn't reach the g5/d4/c5 squares. Ideally, Black would like to put a knight on e6 but it's a bit slow, and the knight may be needed for the battle for the control of the c5-square.} 14. Be3 a5 {Discouraging the typical move b2-b4 which aims to make the d4-square available for a White knight.} 15. Nd2 Nd7 16. b4 {This move should always be calculated, but it doesn't work in this position.} d4 (16... axb4 17. cxb4 d4 $19 {After White retreats the bishop to f2, Black can continue with d4-d3 next.} (17... cxb4 $2 18. Nd4 Ra6 $13)) 17. cxd4 cxb4 18. Ng3 Nb6 $19) 13. Ng3 f6 $17 (13... f5 $17) 14. e6 f5 15. c3 Rf6 16. Qa4 Qd6 17. Na3 Bxe6 18. Be3 Qd7 19. Rad1 Bd6 20. Kh1 Rb8 21. Qc2 Qf7 22. Qf2 Qf8 23. Re2 Rh6 24. Rde1 Bd7 25. Rd2 d4 26. cxd4 cxd4 27. Bxd4 Nxd4 28. Qxd4 Rh4 29. Rf1 Rb4 30. Qd5+ Kh8 31. Nc4 Rh6 32. Nxd6 Rxd6 33. Qc5 Rbb6 34. Rfd1 Qf6 35. Qxc7 Rxd2 36. Rxd2 Be8 37. Qd8 Re6 38. h3 Qg6 39. Kh2 Re3 40. Qg5 Qxg5 41. fxg5 f4 42. Nf5 Re5 43. Rd8 h6 44. Nd6 Kh7 45. Rxe8 Rd5 46. Nf7 Kg6 47. gxh6 gxh6 48. Ne5+ Kf5 49. Nf3 Rd3 50. Rf8+ Ke4 51. Re8+ Kf5 52. Rh8 Re3 53. Rxh6 Re2 54. Rh5+ Ke4 55. Rb5 Kd3 56. Rb7 Rc2 57. Rxa7 Re2 58. Ra3+ Kc2 59. Rb3 Kd1 60. Rb7 Kc1 61. Rd7 Kb1 62. Rc7 Ka1 63. b4 Rd2 64. b5 Rb2 65. b6 Rxa2 66. Rc1+ 1-0

