1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Nd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 Nb8 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Qf3 {Now, Black would like to push c5 but it isn't possible due to the arising tactics with the vulnerable pawn on d5, so Black has two continuations from this position.} Qd7 {Black's idea is either to play Qg4 and exchange queens or to develop the knight to a6 (and if it's possible, reroute it with Na6-Nc5-Ne6) since the c6-pawn is now protected.} (11... a5 12. Bf4 Ra6 {This is also possible to play for Black. The rook stands a bit artificial on a6 but it's very solid and it avoids any potential tactics.}) 12. h3 {Preventing Qg4.} (12. Nce2 {A plan may be to develop with Na6 and reroute it with Na6-Nc5-Ne6, but if Black gets the chance to play c5, then it should be taken.} c5 13. Nb3 Nc6 $17) 12... Na6 $2 (12... Re8 {This is more accurate according to the computer.} 13. Bf4 Na6 14. Rad1 (14. Rfe1 Rb8 $11) 14... Rb8 15. b3 c5 16. Nde2 d4 {Black has a comfortable position.}) 13. Bf4 (13. Nxc6 $3 Qxc6 14. Nxd5 Kh8 15. Nxe7 Qxf3 16. gxf3 Bxh3 17. Rd1 $16) 13... Bb7 14. Qg3 Kh8 {It wasn't necessary to move the king, Black could have simply continued with developing the rook.} (14... Rfe8 $1 {Intending to meet Bh6 with either Bf6 or g6.}) 15. Rfe1 Nc5 16. a4 (16. Bg5 $14) 16... Ne6 17. Nf5 Rg8 18. Nxe7 Qxe7 19. a5 c5 20. a6 Bc6 21. h4 Rab8 22. b3 Rb4 23. Bg5 Qd7 24. Rad1 h6 25. Bc1 Rd4 26. Ne2 Rxd1 27. Rxd1 d4 28. Nf4 Nxf4 29. Bxf4 Qf5 30. Re1 Bd5 31. Re2 Re8 32. Bc1 Re6 33. Ba3 Rg6 34. Qd3 Rxg2+ 35. Kf1 Qg4 36. Ke1 Rg1+ 37. Kd2 Qf4+ 38. Re3 Qxf2+ 39. Re2 Qf4+ 0-1

