{This is a very famous and instructive game about a blockade of a passed pawn, so I decided to include it here due to its educational value and a possible resemblance with an idea proposed in the repertoire.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Re1 Nd7 8. d4 exd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. Bf4 Nc5 11. Qxd8 Bxd8 12. Nc3 f5 $1 13. e5 $2 Ne6 {The knight has arrived on the perfect blockading square and now Black just needs to be careful and avoid giving White the possibility to exchange that powerful knight. That means that Black should take under control the g5, f4, d4, and c5 squares.} 14. Bd2 g5 $3 (14... Bd7 {May allow:} 15. h4 {Controlling the g5-square.}) 15. Ne2 c5 (15... h6 16. Ned4 c5 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 $17 {Even in a scenario such as this one where the knight on e6 has been exchanged, Black is much better since the bishop is also a strong blockader in this situation, and on top of that Black also has the bishop pair and a space advantage.}) 16. Bc3 b5 17. b3 Bb7 18. Ng3 g4 19. Nd2 Be7 20. Nh5 Kf7 $3 21. Nf1 Kg6 22. Nf6 Rad8 23. Rad1 Rxd1 24. Rxd1 Rd8 25. Rxd8 Bxd8 26. Ne3 f4 27. Nd1 Bxf6 28. exf6 Be4 29. Bb2 b4 30. f3 Bxc2 31. Nf2 gxf3 32. gxf3 Bb1 33. Ne4 Bxa2 34. Nd2 a5 35. Kf2 Nd4 36. Bxd4 cxd4 37. Ke2 Kxf6 38. Kd3 Ke5 39. Kc2 a4 40. bxa4 c5 41. a5 c4 42. a6 d3+ 0-1

