1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. O-O {This is another important line that Black needs to know. There are several ways to get to a comfortable position for Black, but the proposed line is simple to play and easy to learn. The following sequence is forced:} Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 {A fascinating move, but it's not good enough.} Qd7 {Black had other alternatives, but this move is good enough.} 9. Nxe4 Be7 {Black is a pawn up and has the bishop pair with an at least equal position.} 10. Bg5 (10. b4 {The opponent can always surprise us with moves like this that seem aggressive and we can't be prepared against all of them. The thing that we need to know is that Black is at least equal and that there must be a good solution to any surprise the opponent can throw at us since the best moves are analyzed.}) 10... O-O (10... f6 $2 11. Bxf6 {White won a pawn since 11...gxf6 runs into 12.Nxf6+.}) 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxd4 Bd7 {This is a theoretical position where Black is doing very well. It's good to note that Black isn't in any danger on the e-file at the moment since wherever the e4-knight moves with a discovered attack, it would abandon the control of some squares.} 13. Nb3 (13. Nc3 Qc5 14. Nb3 Qf5 {Defending the bishop on d7. Black has an at least equal position.} 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Bc6 {Black's bishop is much stronger in comparison to the knight on c3.}) (13. Nb5 {Attacking the c7-pawn and possibly threatening to move the e4-knight with a discovered attack.} Rad8 $15 14. Nxc7 $4 Be6 $19) (13. c3 {This isn't threatening anything, so Black should continue with natural moves such as Rad8 or Rfe8.}) 13... Rad8 (13... Rae8 {This is another good move for Black.} 14. Nec5 Qxe1+ 15. Qxe1 Rxe1+ 16. Rxe1 Bc8 {The position is much easier for Black to play and Black is the one fighting for the advantage.} 17. Nd3 f6 18. f3 Kf7 19. Kf2 Bf5 $15 (19... b6 {Is also possible.})) 14. Nec5 Bc8 15. Rxe7 Rxd1+ 16. Rxd1 Nxe7 17. f3 (17. Nd7 Re8 18. Ne5 f6 19. Nf3 b6 20. c3 c5 $15) 17... b6 18. Ne4 f6 19. Kf2 Kf7 20. Nc3 a6 {Eliminating any Nb5 possibilities and keeping the knights under control.} 21. a3 (21. Nd5 {Black would like to exchange the knight from e7 and enter a bishop against a knight endgame, where Black's bishop would be better.} Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Be6 23. Rd2 c5 24. Rd6 Rb8 {Black's position is simpler to play and Black has the better chances.}) 21... Bf5 22. Nd4 Bg6 23. Rd2 Rd8 24. Ke1 h6 25. Nde2 Rc8 26. h4 Bh7 27. h5 Ke8 28. Nf4 Bg8 29. Nd1 Rd8 30. Ne3 Bf7 31. g4 a5 32. Ke2 Rxd2+ 33. Kxd2 Kd7 34. Kd3 Bg8 35. Kd2 Bh7 36. c4 Kd6 37. b4 axb4 38. axb4 Nc6 39. Kc3 Ne5 40. Nf5+ Bxf5 41. gxf5 Nxf3 42. Ne6 c5 43. Nxg7 Nd4 44. Ne8+ Ke5 45. Nc7 Nxf5 46. Nd5 cxb4+ 47. Kxb4 Ng7 48. Nxb6 Nxh5 49. c5 Nf4 50. Nd7+ Kf5 51. c6 h5 52. Kc4 Ne6 53. Kd5 h4 54. Nf8 Nc7+ 55. Kd6 Nb5+ 56. Kc5 Na7 57. c7 h3 58. Kb6 Nc8+ 59. Kb7 Ne7 60. Ng6 Kxg6 61. c8=Q Nxc8 62. Kxc8 h2 0-1

