{[%evp 0,36,18,18,18,18,18,18,22,10,10,10,2,5,-11,-11,-6,-34,11,11,16,3,10,12,30,49,36,36,26,34,19,38,38,31,31,0,3,-2,7]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 {A playable and interesting line for White ...and a rather...defensive system! White is ready to win a pawn and offer Black the initiative for several moves! In that sense, we often reach positions that are much easer for Black to play because attacking is always easier than defending!} (4. c3 $2 Nxe4 {The maximum White can is to try and equalize. Typically, we will offer to give the pawn back and then gain some initiative.} 5. Bd5 {The simplest way is} Nf6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Bd6 {Black is better due to the two bishops and the pawn structure does not give us a lost pawn ending.} 8. Nf3) (4. O-O $2 {a very common mistake betwen amateur players who....almost played theory!!} Nxe4 {Here follows the typical strategy. We take the pawn and will offer the pawn back at a good moment, sometimes even offering a second pawn in return for the initiative.} 5. Qe2 (5. Re1 {such moves can scare players without a lot of experience.} d5 6. Bb5 {Threatening to take on e5.} (6. Bd3 {This is a very good moment to give the pawn back.} Bd6 (6... Bc5 {is also very good.} 7. Bxe4 dxe4 8. Rxe4 O-O {If White takes the pawn} 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Rxe5 {Black is winning.} Bxf2+ ({Regardless of the move, also} 10... Bd6 11. Re1 {this position resembles a lot of the Marshall-Gambit. Black has very good development, two very active bishops, and very good attacking possibilities for the pawn.} Qh4 12. g3 {We have permanent composition. White will not be able to just exchange all the pieces and win with his extra pawn.}) 11. Kxf2 Qf6+) 7. Bxe4 dxe4 8. Rxe4 O-O {White has a terrible position. Just look at the rook on e4. Our light-square bishop is very strong and Black is almost winning.}) 6... Bc5 {We are ready to give the pawn back and offer another for initiative. Do not memorize this line but understand the idea.} (6... Bd6 {also such a move is very good.} 7. d3 Nf6 8. Nxe5 {White appears to be standing very well but now Black just castles} O-O {and Black has a very nice initiative after} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc6 Bxh2+ 11. Kxh2 Qd6+ 12. Kg1 Qxc6 {Black is a bit better because of the weak White king.}) 7. Nxe5 O-O 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6 Nxf2 {We win.}) 5... d5 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. d3 Nf6 8. Nxe5 O-O {Again, with tremendous compensation.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc6 {Now taking on h2 is the best move, but even} Rb8 {will give us very good compensation with the rook coming to b6 very fast and we have very good attacking possibilites.}) (4. Nc3 $6 {This is the 4 knights Italian which has almost been refuted!} Nxe4 $1 5. Nxe4 (5. O-O $5 {objectively black is better here ...but it is playable for white as a surprise weapon!} Nxc3 6. dxc3 f6 $1 {is practically the best move here.} (6... h6 $5 {is another complicated line.}) ({Michael Adams once played the objectively not so good move} 6... Be7 $6 {against a lower rated opponent.} 7. Qd5 O-O 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Qxe5 d6 10. Qh5 $11) 7. Nh4 g6 8. f4 (8. Re1 d6 $17 9. Nf3 Bd7 10. Be3 Qe7 11. Qd2 Be6 $19 (11... O-O-O $17) 12. Bb5 Bg7 13. Rad1 O-O) 8... Qe7 9. Kh1 (9. fxe5 Qc5+) 9... d6 10. f5 Qg7 $1 $17 11. Bd3 g5 12. Nf3 (12. Qh5+ Qf7) 12... Bd7) (5. Bxf7+ $2 {typical move for coffee house players..and the worst option after 4...Nxe4!} Kxf7 {Black just needs to be a little careful about some cunning ideas.} 6. Nxe4 d5 {Now, obectively, Black is winning.} 7. Nfg5+ (7. Neg5+ Kg8 8. d4 {The first priority is to kick the knight back.} h6 9. Nh3 {Now we can do whatever we want with the knight on h3.} Bg4) 7... Kg8 {We need to be a little bit careful.} 8. Qf3 {Yes, we will defend for a few moves but after that the position is winning.} (8. c3 h6 (8... dxe4 {Please, do not take this.} 9. Qb3+)) 8... Qd7 {The most solid solution.} 9. Nc3 h6 {Now White is forced to move the knight back which is needed in the attack.} 10. Nh3 {Forced.} Nd4 11. Qd1 Qf7 {This is a winning position for Black.}) 5... d5 6. Bd3 {This is pretty much the only move.} (6. Bb5 $2 dxe4 7. Nxe5 Qd5 {Black has a big advantage.} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. d4 (9. Ng4 {The doubled-pawns here are irrelevant because dynamic factors are working for us: Two very strong bishops, fast development, and an annoying pawn on e4. The doubled-pawns are also on a closed file which means that they cannot be attacked by a rook.} Ba6 $17 10. Ne3 Qe5) 9... f6 $17 10. Ng4 (10. Qh5+ $4 g6 11. Nxg6 Qxh5) 10... Bd6 (10... Bxg4 $5 11. Qxg4 f5 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qe2 Bd6 $17) 11. Ne3 Qf7 12. O-O O-O 13. c4 Be6 14. c5 Be7 $17) 6... dxe4 {The simplest move.} 7. Bxe4 Bd6 8. O-O O-O {This is a playable position. If your opponent plays this position, he is probably not a very strong player.} 9. Re1 {Usually, the play this move.} (9. Bxc6 bxc6 {Here again Black is better because the two-doubled pawns are on a closed file and Black has very strong bishops, especially the light-squared one.}) ({It is good that White cannot play} 9. d4 $2 {because we capture with the knight.} Nxd4 $17) 9... Qf6 $5 {Good and simple.} ({There is an unusal and wonderful move as well here.} 9... Nb4 $5 {This move only exists because my computer says so. We will play f5 on the next move no matter what.} 10. d4 (10. c3 $5 {Again we play} f5 11. Bb1 (11. cxb4 fxe4 12. Rxe4 Bf5 {We don't care about the pawn structure. We have very strong compensation and initiative.}) 11... e4 12. cxb4 exf3 13. Qxf3 Kh8 $1 $15) (10. a3 f5 $36) 10... f5 {Black is at least equal.}) 10. d3 h6 $1 {Preventing any Bg5 ideas.} 11. Bd2 Bd7 12. Bc3 Rae8 $132) 4... d5 (4... Nxe4 {This is a funny line which is objectively losing for Black but it is very good for blitz.} 5. Nxe4 (5. Nxf7 Qh4 {and suprisingly Black is better.}) ({Now White needs to find} 5. Bxf7+ {after any other move White is worse surprisingly.} Ke7 6. d3 Nf6 7. Bb3 d5 {Yes, we are objectively losing, but for a Blitz game this is playable. The next move will be h6, we have a bad king but White's pieces are also kind of clumpsy.}) 5... d5 {Black is immediatedly better.}) 5. exd5 Na5 {Objectively, the best move.} ({Lately, this old line with} 5... b5 {is considered to be kind of interesting. The best move, suprisingly, is} 6. Bf1 Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qc5 8. Bxb5 Bb7) 6. Bb5+ (6. d3 $6 {this is not a good move...BUT I MUST KNOW IT!!} h6 7. Nf3 e4 8. Qe2 Nxc4 9. dxc4 Bc5 10. O-O O-O $15 {With a very nice initiative. Generally in such positions, we will be a pawn down but it is not a problem because we will have a very strong initiative.}) 6... c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 {This is the initial position. There are four moves here. In my opinion, only one is good and one is acceptable.} 8. Bd3 $1 {The best move by far for concrete reasons.} (8. Be2 {the old main line which is decent, too!} h6 9. Nf3 (9. Nh3 {This move has been played many times by Bobby Fischer. Objectively, it is not a good move.} g5 {This move is under-estimated by the computer. The idea is Bg7 and 0-0. The other idea is that White cannot castle because g4. Sooner or later, White will have to play Ng1.} ({A simple way to play is} 9... Bxh3 10. gxh3 Bc5 $36 {with a lot of compensation.}) 10. d3 (10. O-O g4) 10... Bg7 {Our plan is to castle short and then do something with our knight, either to play Nb7 or c5 followed by Nc6. Our rook will possibly go to b8.} 11. Nc3 (11. O-O g4) 11... O-O {It does not matter what the computer will tell you here. Practically, Black has a very good game and no one can play perfectly for White for too long.} 12. Ng1 {Our plan, generally, is to play Nd5 and f5.} Rb8 $1 {Stopping any b4 ideas and preventing the Bc1 from being developed.} ({But we don't want to play} 12... Nd5 {immediatedly because there is this little annoying move} 13. h4 $1 {We should not allow the rook to enter the game from h1.}) 13. Nf3 ({We want to be able to answer} 13. h4 {with} g4) 13... Nd5 14. O-O (14. h4 g4 15. Nd2 f5 $40 {Practically, this position is much easier to play for Black.}) 14... Re8 $1 {intending f5 with very good compensation for Black. If we lose the game, we won't lose it because White has an extra pawn on c2.} (14... f5)) 9... e4 10. Ne5 Bc5 $1 {I saw this line first in Victor Bologan's book several years ago. This move threatens Qd4 and forces White to play} (10... Bd6 {of course...there s nothing wrong with this move ...its just another variation!}) 11. c3 {We give him an extra move and now we go} Qc7 $3 (11... Bd6 $1) 12. d4 (12. f4 {A rare move which somebody played in a blitz game against me.} Bb6 {This is the best move according to the computer. We have very good compensation because White cannot castle.} (12... exf3 13. Nxf3 Ng4 14. b4 (14. d4 Bd6 $36 15. b4 Nb7) 14... Bd6 15. bxa5 Bxh2) 13. b4 (13. d4 exd3 $17) 13... Nb7 14. Qa4 Bd7 $15) 12... exd3 13. Nxd3 Bd6 {we offered white the c2-c3 move for free..but now the knight on d3 is unstable! .....} 14. h3 (14. g3 O-O 15. O-O Bf5 16. Be3 (16. Be3 Rad8) (16. Bf4 Rad8 $17) 16... Rfe8 $15 17. Nd2 Nd5 (17... Bxg3 18. hxg3 Rxe3 $11) (17... Rad8 $36) 18. Bd4 c5 19. c4 Nb6 20. Bc3 Naxc4 $15) (14. b4 Nb7 15. h3 a5) 14... O-O 15. O-O Bf5 $15 {We have very fast development, the rooks come to the center, and no other knowledge is needed.} 16. b4 (16. Nd2 Rad8 17. Nf3 c5 (17... Rfe8)) 16... Nb7 17. Nd2 a5 $15) (8. Qf3 $6 {This used to be played a few times in the past.} cxb5 $1 {This is good.. but maybe its too much troubl for nothing! ...many thngs to memorize while 8... Be7! is simple and good...with very nice compensation for the...2 missing pawns!} (8... Be7 $1 9. Bxc6+ Nxc6 10. Qxc6+ Bd7 11. Qf3 Rc8 $1 12. Nc3 {We are two pawns down, but we have a lead in development and a pawn in the center with another coming to f5 very soon.} Bc6 $1 {with a very good initiative for black!!} (12... O-O $1 $15 13. O-O Ng4 {Just to include our f-pawn.} 14. Nh3 Rc6 {Our rook is added to the attack.} (14... Bd6))) 9. Qxa8 Qc7 10. Qf3 {it seems that black is doing very well here...in ths...totally unclear position} (10. Nc3 $2 {The queen will be trapped.} Nc6 11. Nxb5 Qd7 $17 12. O-O Be7 13. d4 O-O 14. dxe5 Ba6 {Black is better, almost winning.} 15. Qxf8+ Bxf8 16. exf6 Bxb5) (10. Ne4 $2 Nc6 11. Nxf6+ gxf6 12. Nc3 Kd7 $3 $19 13. Nxb5 (13. Nd5 Qd6 14. Ne3 Ba6 15. O-O Bg7 16. Nf5 Rxa8 17. Nxd6 Kxd6) 13... Qb6 14. Nc3 Bb7) 10... Nc6 $1 11. c3 {only move!} Bg4 $1 (11... Nd4) 12. Qg3 (12. Qe3 $2 h6 13. Ne4 Nd5 14. Qg3 f5 $17 15. f3 Nf4 $1 (15... Bh5 $17) 16. fxg4 fxe4) 12... Nd4 $1 13. Na3 $1 Ne2 (13... Bxa3 $4 {This is a mistake because after} 14. cxd4 $18 {It is White who is winning.}) 14. Qd3 Nf4 15. Qxb5+ Bd7 16. Qc4 Qb7 $3 17. Qxf7+ (17. f3 Bxa3 18. bxa3 O-O $36) 17... Kd8 18. f3 (18. Rg1 $2 Bxa3 19. bxa3 Qa6 20. c4 Nd3+ 21. Ke2 Nf4+ 22. Ke1 Be8 23. Qxg7 Rg8 24. Qh6 Rg6 25. Qh4 Qxc4 $19) 18... Bxa3 19. Qc4 (19. bxa3 $2 Qa6 20. c4 Be8 21. Qxg7 Rg8 22. Qh6 Rg6 23. Qh4 Qxc4 (23... Nxg2+)) (19. Qb3 Qa6) 19... Be7 $3 20. Nf7+ Ke8 21. Nxe5 (21. Nxh8 $4 Nxg2+ 22. Kd1 (22. Kf2 Nh4 $3 $19 23. Qxh4 Ng4+) 22... Ne3+ 23. dxe3 Qxf3+ 24. Kc2 Bf5+ 25. Kb3 Qb7+ 26. Ka4 Bd7+) 21... Nxg2+ 22. Kd1 Bb5 23. Qd4 Nd7 24. Nxd7 Bxd7 25. d3 Rf8 $19) (8. Ba4 $2 {This move is almost losing by force but we need to know what to do.} h6 (8... Bb4) 9. Nf3 e4 10. Ne5 (10. Ng1 Bc5 $17 {Just castle and attack brutally and you will see that things are not scary for Black after all despite being a pawn down.} 11. Ne2 Ng4 12. O-O Qh4 {Black is winning material.}) 10... Qd4 $3 11. Bxc6+ Nxc6 12. Nxc6 Qc5 13. Nxa7 Qxa7 $19 {White has three pawns for the piece but Black is winning as we have two very strong bishops and an attack.}) 8... Nd5 (8... Nb7 $6) 9. Nf3 $5 {THIS IS THE MAIN LINE OF THE MAIN LINE OF THE MAIN LINE !!} (9. h4 h6 $1 {IS AN ...ALMOST FORCED DRAW !} (9... g6 $5 {LESS EXPLORED BUT GOOD! DO NOT WORRY TOO MUCH ABOUT CONCRETE THEORY! ...EVEN IF YOU FORGET IT, WHITE HS VERY DIFFICULT MOVES TO MAKE AND THE POSITION IS A LOT EASIER FOR BLACK TO PLAY!} 10. Nc3 (10. Qf3 $6 f5 {But we are not really threatening e5-e4 because of Bxe4.} 11. Nc3 (11. O-O h6 $17) 11... Nb4 $36) (10. O-O Bg7 11. Re1 O-O $132 12. Bf1 h6 13. Nf3 Bg4 {This is practically very difficult for White. We only need to correct the knight somehow.}) 10... h6 $5 11. Nxd5 (11. Nf3 Bg7 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 $36 {You do not need to memorize these lines.}) 11... cxd5 12. Nf3 Bg7 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7 15. d4 f6 $3 $132 16. O-O e4 (16... O-O)) 10. Qh5 $1 {White has to play that move.} (10. Nf3 $2 Bd6 $17 {The h4-h6 addition is clearly in Black's favor.} 11. O-O O-O {Black has a tremendous advantage. Our plan is f5 or Bg4 first.}) 10... Qf6 11. Ne4 ({Surprisingly, he cannot take on f7} 11. Nxf7 $4 {All of this is very well known.} Nf4 12. Nd6+ Kd7 13. Qe8+ Kxd6 $19 {Black is winning easily because White has not developed any pieces.}) (11. Nh7 $2 Rxh7 12. Bxh7 g6 13. Qd1 Qg7) 11... Qe6 (11... Qe7 $5 {if we want to contnue the battle!} 12. Nbc3 (12. Be2 g6 13. Qf3 f5 14. Nec3 Nb4 15. Bd1 Be6 $132) 12... Nf4 13. Qf3 Qd7 $1 $132 14. Bf1 f5 15. Ng3 Bd6 $132) 12. Ng5 Qf6) (9. Ne4 $6 Nf4 10. Bf1 f5 11. Ng3 (11. Nec3 Bc5 $15) 11... Bc5 $15 12. c3 Bb6) 9... Bd6 $1 10. O-O O-O $5 {THIS IS ALSO INTERSTING !} (10... Nf4 $1 {OBJECTIVELY THIS MIGHT BE THE BEST...AND IT LEADS TO A FORCED DRAW..OR TO VERY EQUAL POSITIONS!} 11. Re1 (11. Be2 $2 {This is a very well known mistake.} Nxg2 $3 12. Kxg2 e4 $17) 11... Nxd3 12. cxd3 O-O 13. Nxe5 (13. Nc3) (13. b3 {The most common result in such positions is a draw.} c5 14. Ba3 (14. Bb2 $2 f6 $17) 14... Nc6 15. Nc3 Bg4 $132) 13... c5 14. Nc3 Bb7 {AND THE PLAN IS USUALLY f5!! followed by Rf6 and Rg6 or Rh6} 15. b3 (15. Nf3 Nc6 $36 (15... f5)) 15... f5 $1 16. Bb2 Rf6 17. Nf3 (17. Nb5 Bxe5 18. Rxe5 Rg6 19. f3 Nc6 20. Rxc5 Nb4 $17) 17... Rg6) 11. Re1 (11. Nc3 $6 f5 $15 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Be2 e4 $36) 11... Re8 $1 12. Nc3 (12. a3 $6 f5 13. b4 e4 14. bxa5 exf3 $17) 12... f5 $1 13. Nxd5 (13. Bf1 e4 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Nd4 Qf6 (15... Qh4 16. g3 Qf6 17. c3 Nc4 18. d3 Ne5 $132) 16. c3 Bb7 $132 (16... Nc4 $132 17. d3 Ne5)) 13... cxd5 14. Bb5 Bd7 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. d3 (16. d4 e4 17. Ne5 (17. Nd2) 17... Bxe5 18. dxe5 Nc6 19. Bf4 (19. f4 exf3 20. Qxf3 Nxe5) 19... Qe6 $1 $17 20. Qd2 Nxe5) 16... Nc6 {With good compensation and nice attacking chances for Black} 17. c4 (17. Bd2 $1 e4 $17 18. Ng5 h6 19. Nh3 Rad8) (17. c3 a5 18. Qb3 (18. a4 $6 Bc7 $15) 18... Bc7 $132 19. a4 Rab8 20. Qc2 e4 (20... e4) (20... h6) 21. dxe4 dxe4 (21... fxe4 $15) 22. Nd4 Bxh2+ 23. Kxh2 Qc7+ 24. Kg1 Nxd4) (17. b3 Rad8 18. Bg5 Rc8 $36) 17... d4 18. Bd2 (18. Qa4 Bc5 $132) 18... Rab8 $132 (18... a5 $132) *

