1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 Nd5 9. Nf3 ({After} 9. h4 {I may repeat.} h6 10. Nf3 {This is wrong.} Bd6 {It is a very improved version of this line.}) 9... Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 f5 {Re8 intending f5 is also playable.} 12. Nxe5 Qf6 13. Nf3 g5 {It is the best move for Black.} 14. c4 {14.g3 is supposed to be the best move here.} Nf4 15. Bf1 g4 16. d4 {White is going to sacrifice a piece and gets some pawns.} gxf3 17. Qxf3 Ne6 18. Qc3 Nb7 19. c5 Bc7 20. b4 {Around here the theory stops as "unclear". We can keep on analyzing but I don't think is necessary.} a5 21. b5 Qxd4 22. Qxd4 Nxd4 23. Bc4+ Be6 24. Bxe6+ Nxe6 25. Rxe6 Nxc5 26. Re2 Rfe8 27. Nc3 cxb5 28. Be3 Be5 29. Bxc5 Bxc3 30. Rxe8+ Rxe8 31. Rb1 b4 32. Kf1 {This game is very educative.} Re5 33. Be3 a4 34. Rc1 a3 35. g3 Rb5 {35...Bb2 would be a draw.} 36. Rc2 b3 37. axb3 Rxb3 {Black is good winning chances as White's extra pawn on the kingside is of no relevance.} 38. Kg2 Kf7 39. Bd2 Be5 40. Bf4 Bxf4 41. gxf4 {Here Black should try to put his rook behind the passed pawn.} Rb7 42. Ra2 Ra7 43. Kg3 Ra4 {99% such endgames are winning.} 44. Kh4 Kg6 45. Kg3 Kf6 46. h3 h5 47. Kh4 Kg6 48. Kg3 Kg7 49. Kf3 h4 50. Ke2 Kf6 51. Kd1 Ke6 52. Kc1 Kd5 53. Kb1 Ke4 54. Rd2 Kf3 55. Ka2 Kg2 0-1

