1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 {You need to remember a couple of moves.} Nd5 9. Nf3 (9. Ne4 {we play} f5 {with compensation}) 9... Bd6 10. O-O Nf4 {is objectively the best move.} (10... O-O {is playable} 11. Re1 {and then either the crazy f5 or Re8.}) 11. Re1 Nxd3 12. cxd3 O-O 13. Nxe5 c5 {For an experienced player, it is immediatedly obvious that draw is a possible result because we are two pawns down but White's position is horrible. The pawns and compensation neutralize each other and it should be a draw.} 14. d4 {It is an acceptable move, somehow restoring coordination.} cxd4 15. d3 Bb7 16. Nd2 Bxe5 {Taking and Nc6 is a common idea.} 17. Rxe5 Nc6 18. Re1 Qd5 {With some compensation.} 19. Qb3 {This is very bad.} (19. Nf3 Rfe8 {At this moment, threatening Ne5 and there is compensation for the pawn.}) 19... Nb4 {A very good move for Black. Spotting these kind of attacks is far more important than memorizing lines.} 20. Qxd5 Bxd5 {Now there are too many threats.} 21. Rd1 {Because it is a blitz game, White blundered and Black won very fast.} Nc2 22. Rb1 Bxa2 23. b3 Bxb1 24. Nxb1 Rab8 25. Nd2 Rfe8 26. Kf1 a5 27. h4 Rec8 28. Nc4 Rxb3 29. Nxa5 Rb1 30. Nc4 h5 31. Ke2 Nb4 32. Kd2 Rb3 33. Ke2 Re8+ 34. Kf1 Rxd3 35. Bd2 Nd5 36. Ra1 Nc3 37. Ra5 Rc8 38. Nd6 Rxd2 0-1

