1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Be2 h6 9. Nf3 e4 10. Ne5 Bd6 11. d4 (11. Nc4 {We have good compensation after} Nxc4 12. Bxc4 O-O {Maybe with some ideas to sacrifice. We are out of book now. Let's say he is afraid and plays} 13. h3 {The general characteristics of the position remain. Fast development, an annoying pawn on e4, and chances for an attack.} Qe7 {We want to play Qe5 if he castles and it also stops d4.}) 11... exd3 12. Nxd3 {I would have preferred this position with a pawn on c3, but this is also playable.} O-O 13. O-O Qc7 {Controlling the important diagonal.} 14. h3 c5 {Practically, this is a very good position for Black that is very easy to play. What does White have to show for all of Black's fast development? A pawn on b2.} 15. b3 c4 16. bxc4 Nxc4 {With good compensation.} 17. Nd2 Nxd2 18. Bxd2 Bf5 {Of course, the White player is also a GM and has studied these positions.} 19. Bf3 Rac8 20. Re1 Rfd8 {We put the rooks in the center with lots of compensation.} 21. a4 Qxc2 22. Nb4 Qb2 23. Nc6 Rxc6 24. Bxc6 Bb4 25. Qf3 Bxd2 26. Rf1 Qe5 27. Ra3 Bc2 28. Bb5 Be4 29. Qe2 Bb4 30. Rd3 Bd6 0-1

