1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 {The problem for Black is that it is objectively equal if they play the best moves. It is very drawish. We would like an unclear position. There is no space for objectively good but tricky novelties.} Nd5 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O {Here I tried several moves, even g5 but it is not working.} Nf4 {We have to play this or 0-0.} 11. Nc3 Nxd3 12. cxd3 O-O {With compensation for the pawn.} 13. Ne4 c5 {Quite often we give that bishop.} 14. Qc2 {does not seem necessary.} (14. b3 {appears more natural.}) 14... Nc6 {This appears to be very strong.} 15. Qa4 (15. Nxc5 {There are two very good moves here for Black.} Nb4 {The White queen seems to be misplaced on c2.} (15... Bg4 {appears to be also very strong because we want to target the d4-square.} 16. Nb7 Qc7 17. Nxd6 Qxd6) 16. Qc3 Bxc5 17. Qxc5 Nxd3 {Black is, for sure, better.}) 15... Bb7 16. Re1 Nb4 17. a3 Nxd3 {With a very strong attack.} 18. Re3 Nf4 19. b4 Bxe4 {This means concrete play.} 20. Rxe4 cxb4 21. axb4 f5 22. Rxf4 exf4 23. d4 Qe7 {White had to sacrifice and now there is just a little bit of compensation.} 24. Bd2 h6 25. Re1 Qf7 26. Ne5 Bxe5 27. dxe5 f3 28. Qc6 Rad8 29. Be3 Rfe8 30. Qxf3 Rxe5 31. Ra1 Qd5 32. h3 Qxf3 33. gxf3 Rb5 34. Rxa7 Rxb4 35. f4 Rb1+ 36. Kg2 Rd6 37. Ra5 Rg6+ 38. Kh2 Rbg1 39. h4 R6g2+ 40. Kh3 Rg4 41. Rxf5 g6 42. Rc5 h5 43. Kh2 R4g2+ 44. Kh3 Rg4 45. Kh2 Ra1 46. f5 gxf5 47. Rxf5 Rxh4+ 48. Kg3 Rah1 49. Kg2 Rb1 50. Bf4 Rg4+ 51. Bg3 h4 52. Rf4 Rxf4 53. Bxf4 Rb4 54. Bd6 Rd4 55. Be5 Re4 56. f4 Re3 57. Bf6 h3+ 58. Kh2 Kf7 59. Bh4 Kg6 60. Bg3 Kh5 61. Kxh3 Rf3 62. f5 Rxf5 63. Kg2 Kg4 64. Be1 Rf3 65. Bf2 Ra3 66. Bc5 Ra2+ 67. Kg1 Kf3 68. Bd6 Ra6 69. Bc7 Rc6 70. Bb8 Rg6+ 71. Kh2 Rg2+ 72. Kh1 Rg8 73. Bc7 Kf2 74. Bb6+ Kg3 75. Kg1 Rc8 76. Bf2+ Kh3 77. Bb6 Rc2 78. Bd4 Rg2+ 79. Kf1 Kg3 80. Be5+ Kf3 81. Bf6 Rg6 82. Be5 Rg5 83. Bf6 Rf5 84. Ba1 Rb5 0-1

