1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 {This is necessary, as the e4-pawn is really under attack in this position:} (4. O-O $2 Nxe4 $1 5. Qe2 (5. Re1 d5 6. Bb5 (6. Bd3 Bd6 7. Bxe4 dxe4 8. Rxe4 O-O $17) 6... Bc5 7. d4 exd4 8. Nxd4 O-O $19) (5. d4 d5 6. Bb5 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Re1 Be7 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bd3 Nc5 $17) 5... d5 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. d3 Nf6 8. Nxe5 O-O $1 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc6 Bxh2+ 11. Kh1 (11. Kxh2 Qd6+ $17) 11... Rb8 12. g3 Qd6 13. Ba4 Rb4 14. Nc3 Bxg3 15. fxg3 Qxg3 $19) (4. Nc3 Nxe4 $11) 4... h6 $5 {This move, which somewhat looks like beginner's play, may require some explanation. Generally speaking, in the opening it is important to develop one's pieces quickly and avoid unnecessary pawn moves. Especially when you are Black, moves that neglect development often get punished. So why is this one an exception? First of all, in this particular type of position, moves that are suited to punish slow play would be Ng5 and d2-d4. One has just been prevented and the other has lost a lot of its punch due to the fact that the pawn has just moved to d3. d3-d4 ideas may come into consideration later, when Black further neglects his development, but for now they are harmless. But to understand the concept, it is important to know a few things about Black's kingside bishop. In the Italian and in the Ruy Lopez, this bishop is usually developed to either c5 or e7. In the latter case, a well-known manoeuvre is Re8, Bf8, g7-g6, Bg7. Many players execute this delayed fianchetto almost automatically, never wondering why they had not put the bishop there in the first place. The reason why this is seen so often is simple: g7 is generally speaking the best square for the king's bishop in the Italian and Ruy Lopez. As White's plans are usually connected with playing d3-d4 at some point, the bishop will be well placed to defend the centre, generate pressure on the opponent's centre and roam freely on the long diagonal once the position opens. The reason why it is rarely played early is also simple: In the open games, slow moves like g7-g6 can often get refuted with energetic play. Back to the Italian with 4...h6: The point of this move is to slowly prepare a kingside fianchetto (usually g7-g6 but sometimes even g7-g5) by first of all preventing White from playing Ng5. Now the reader may wonder: Why should I play such a slow system, that requires three pawn moves before development can be continued? The answer to this question is: It's much less slow than it seems. In setups with Be7, Black will certainly be able to castle and look developed quickly, but if he proceeds to play the bishop back to f8 and then to g7, the tempo-count does not look so favourable anymore. And when the bishop is developed to c5 instead, the a-pawn has to move to create a retreat square on a7, soon followed by the bishop moving back to a7. And as the bishop is missing on the kingside, at some point the notion of its white counterpart on g5, creating an unpleasant pin, becomes unpleasant and Black decides to prevent this by playing h7-h6. So this is what the 4...h6 variation is about: Obtain the best possible placement for the king's bishop and pay the smallest possible price in development tempi for it. But it has to be paid immediately!} 5. O-O (5. c3 d6 {should transpose.}) (5. d4 $6 {This is almost identical to the (harmless) 4.d4, with the difference that in some lines the pawn on h6 is actually useful, preventing Bg5 or Ng5.} exd4 6. e5 d5 7. Bb5 Ne4 $1 8. Nxd4 Bd7 $132) 5... d6 {It is necessary to stabilise the centre before executing the fianchetto.} (5... g6 $2 6. d4 $1 $16) (5... g5 $2 6. d4 $1 $16) 6. c3 $1 ({White has many moves at his disposal that can be mixed with each other and lead to transpositions, like a2-a4, c2-c3, Nbd2 and Re1.} 6. h3 $2 {may look like it but is not one of those moves.} g5 $1 {Not having castled yet, Black is in a great position to start a kingside attack and exploit the weakness that White has created with his previous move.} 7. c3 g4 8. hxg4 Bxg4 9. Nbd2 Qd7 10. Re1 Rg8 $17 {Black will eventually castle queenside, where his king will be perfectly safe. White's king on the other hand is in a much less secure spot due to the pressure on the semi-open f-file}) ({An interesting point is the following:} 6. a4 g6 7. h3 $2 g5 $3 {Counter-intuitive but perfectly logical: Having established that after 6.h3, 6...g7-g5 leads to a clear advantage for Black, it shouldn't come as a surprise that the advance of White's a-pawn hardly changes the evaluation.} 8. a5 a6 9. c3 g4 10. hxg4 Bxg4 11. Nbd2 (11. Qb3 Qd7 12. Qxb7 Ra7 $1 13. Qb3 Bxf3 14. gxf3) 11... Rg8 $17) ({After} 6. Nc3 {, Black can win the pair of bishops} Na5 $1 {, with a promising position:} 7. Bb3 (7. a4 Nxc4 8. dxc4 Be7 9. Qe2 (9. c5 O-O 10. cxd6 cxd6 $3 $15) 9... c6 10. Rd1 Qc7 $11) 7... Nxb3 8. axb3 c5 $1 $132 (8... c6 9. Be3 a5 $132)) 6... g6 {White has four different ways to play this position: 1) Quiet and slow development with the intention to avoid concrete action until later in the middlegame (Guccio Piano style). This is not only harmless for Black, but White also runs the risk of ending up worse. The manoeuvre Nd2-f1-g3 not only costs a lot of time but also tends to be ineffective against a kingside fianchetto - the f5-square is not available for the knight and Black's king is perfectly safe. In the meantime, Black will sooner or later stand ready to either play d6-d5 or f7-f5 and take over the initiative. 2) Queenside expansion with c2-c3 and b2-b4. This is generally rather slow (note that there is no bishop on c5 that White can chase around) and, similarly to 1), invites Black to become active in the centre or on the kingside again. 3) Delayed d3-d4 - White continues development and expands in the centre at a certain point. This gives Black enough time to stabilise his position, castle and fight back in the centre. 4) Quick d2-d4 - White plays c2-c3 and d3-d4 immediately. This is the critical line. Black should be OK here, but he has to play accurately.} (6... g5 $5 {This may be more of a coffeehouse move, leading to wild and chaotic positions. Maybe not the best choice against computer preparation but it looks fun and certainly playable in a practical game.}) 7. d4 $1 {White's only dangerous approach: 4) Striking in the centre immediately.} (7. a4 {This move is usually played as part of plan 2) queenside expansion.} Bg7 (7... a5 $2 {is positionally sound but leads to concrete problems after} 8. d4 $1 $16 {Now the inclusion of a2-a4 and a7-a5 works in White's favour after the critical} Nxe4 9. Bb5 Bd7 10. dxe5 {, and the bishop is protected whenever Black plays Nxe5. Thus, as a general rule, Black should not play a7-a5 before the bishop is on g7 and he is ready to castle.}) 8. Re1 {Now} ({After} 8. b4 $5 {, possible continuations are} O-O 9. Nbd2 (9. b5 Na5 $1 10. Ba2 b6 $132 ({Also good is} 10... a6 $1 $132) 11. Nbd2 a6 $132) 9... a6 $5 (9... Nh5 $5) (9... Kh8 $5 10. a5 a6 11. Re1 Nh7 12. Nf1 f5 $36 13. exf5 (13. h3 f4 14. d4 g5 $17 (14... Ng5 $36)) 13... gxf5 14. Ng3 f4 15. Nh5 Bg4 16. Nxg7 Kxg7 $40) 10. Bb3 Nh5 11. Nc4 Kh7 12. Ne3 Nf4 $132 13. Nd5 $2 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 f5 $15) (8. a5 {should generally be answered with} a6) 8... a5 {is perfectly playable.} ({But there is also nothing wrong with} 8... O-O)) (7. Nbd2 $5 Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Nf1 $6 (9. d4 $2 {Plan 3) Delayed d3-d4 at its worst: Black is fully developed and White's bishop is still standing on c4.} exd4 10. cxd4 d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 $15 {Black's pieces are perfectly placed to fight the IQP while White's queen's knight is misplaced on d2.}) (9. Bb3 {Now Black has several good continuations:} Na5 $5 (9... a5 $5) (9... Re8 $1 10. Nf1 Be6 11. Bxe6 Rxe6 12. Ng3 a5 $11 (12... d5 $11)) 10. Bc2 c5) 9... Na5 10. Bb5 a6 11. Ba4 b5 12. Bc2 c5 13. Ng3 Re8 14. h3 Bb7 {White has arranged his pieces in 1) Guiccio Piano style. With no perspectives on the kingside or on the queenside, it seems logical to move forward in the centre. But this plays right into the strenghts of Black's setup:} 15. d4 $2 exd4 16. cxd4 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Rc8 $17 {All of Black's pieces are active and White is under huge pressure, for example} 18. Bf4 (18. Rb1 d5 19. e5 Ne4 $17 20. Nxe4 (20. e6 $4 Bxd4 21. exf7+ Kxf7 22. Qxd4 Rxc2 23. Bxh6 Qf6 24. Nxe4 dxe4 $1 $19) 20... dxe4 21. Bxe4 Rc4 $1 22. Bxb7 Rxd4 23. Qf3 Rxe5 24. Rxe5 Rd1+ 25. Kh2 Bxe5+ 26. g3 Nxb7 27. Qxb7 Bxg3+ 28. fxg3 Qd3 $19) 18... h5 $1 (18... Nc4 $1 19. b3 Na3 $17) 19. Bg5 Qb6 20. Be3 Nc4 $19) ({A better attempt at implementing plan 3) is} 7. Re1 Bg7 8. d4 O-O $1 {So it turns out that 3) offers White nothing better than the type of open d-file equal position that arises after} 9. dxe5 ({Now} 9. Bb3 $6 {, preventing exd4 and d6-d5, looks logical, but leads to problems after both} Bg4 $1 (9... exd4 $1 10. Nxd4 (10. cxd4 Bg4 $15) 10... Re8 $1 $15 {and}) 10. d5 Ne7 $132) 9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 $11 {Of course, this equal endgame still offers chances to play for a win, for example after} 12. f3 Bd7 13. a4 a5 14. Be3 Bf8 15. Nd2 Kg7 16. Bb3 Be8 $1 17. Nc4 Nd7 {, intending to play Bc5 and later reach a favourable knight vs. Italian bishop position.}) 7... Qe7 $1 {This is the concession Black has to make against White's precise and energetic play: Another patient non-development move, necessary to keep the central tension.} 8. Re1 {White should also maintain the tension while creating a vis-a-vis of rook and queen. Other moves are harmless.} (8. dxe5 Nxe5 $1 {As a general rule, this is usually the correct recapture with a bishop on g7. If White refuses to trade knights on e5 now, Black's king's bishop will be happy on g7.} 9. Nxe5 dxe5 $11 10. Re1 (10. f3 $4 Qc5+ $19) (10. Qe2 Bg7 11. f3 O-O 12. Be3 Nh5 $132) 10... Bg7 11. a4 O-O $5 12. a5 Bd7 $11) (8. d5 $6 {If White plays d4-d5 in this line, Black usually has a good version of the King's Indian defence. White is a long way from creating any threats on the queensides while Black's attack, starting with f7-f5, is ready to start in a few moves, for example} Nb8 $1 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. c4 O-O 11. Nc3 a5 12. Bd2 Na6 $132 13. Re1 Nh7 (13... Nd7 $1 14. a3 Nb6 $5 {Preventing b2-b4 by protecting the a8-rook and threatening Nc5, followed by a5-a4.})) 8... Bg7 9. h3 {In view of the central tension, this prophylaxis against Bg4 makes a lot of sense.} (9. dxe5 Nxe5 $1 {This line shows another aspect of Nxe5 being the correct recapture: Freeing the c-pawn.} 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. b3 $6 O-O 12. Ba3 {This looks good but hardly achieves anything. The bishop just ends up rather misplaced on a3.} c5 13. Nd2 Rd8 $36 14. Qc2 Bd7 15. Bd3 b5 $132 (15... h5 $5 16. Rad1 Bh6 $132)) (9. Nbd2 O-O 10. h3 {is probably best, transposing to the mainline.} (10. Nf1 Bg4 $1 11. d5 (11. dxe5 Nxe5 $15 12. Be2 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Rfe8 $15) 11... Nb8 12. h3 Bc8 $5 $132 13. Bd3 c6 ({Also good is} 13... a5 14. c4 Na6) 14. c4 a5 15. Bd2 Nbd7 $132) (10. Bd3 Nh7 $1 {Increasing the pressure in the centre and forcing white to resolve the tension.} 11. d5 {Again, Black has nothing to be afraid of in this King's Indian structure.} (11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 $11) 11... Nb8 12. Nf1 a5 13. Ng3 h5 $1 14. h3 Na6 $132)) 9... O-O 10. Nbd2 a5 {As often after the king as found safety, Black has several alternatives.} (10... Bd7 $5) (10... a6 $5 11. Nf1 b5 12. Bd3 (12. Bb3 Na5 13. Bc2 c5 $132) 12... Bd7 13. Ng3 Rfb8 14. Be3 a5 $132 (14... Nd8 $132)) 11. Nf1 (11. a4 exd4 (11... b6 $5 12. Nf1 exd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 $132) 12. cxd4 Qd8) 11... a4 12. Ng3 (12. Bb5 Bd7 13. Bxa4 $2 Nxd4 $15) 12... Bd7 13. Bd3 Rfc8 (13... b5 $5 14. Bxb5 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 exd4 16. Bxd7 Nxd7 17. cxd4 c5 $1 $132) 14. Be3 Kh7 15. Qd2 Na5 $132 {The computer may find White slightly preferable in these positions after 7.d4 Qe7, but it is not at all easy to prove anything or even come up with a good plan. Play is unusually double-edged for the Italian, which makes it a good line to play for a win with Black.} *

