1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. d3 h6 5. O-O d6 6. c3 g6 7. Re1 Bg7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Nf1 Na5 $1 10. Bb5 a6 11. Ba4 b5 12. Bc2 c5 13. d4 $2 {White underestimates the power of his opponent's pieces after the position opens up. Now Black has two ways to get the upper hand.} exd4 14. cxd4 Bg4 $1 $15 ({Also good is the double-capture} 14... cxd4 $1 15. Nxd4 Bb7 $15 {, for example} 16. Ng3 Rc8 17. Rb1 Re8 18. b3 d5 $1 19. e5 Ne4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 Bxe5 $3 23. Bf4 Bxf4 24. Rxf4 Re5 $15) 15. d5 {With the queenside majority in motion and White's pieces mostly misplaced, this is a very good Benoni for Black.} (15. dxc5 dxc5 16. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $15 {is also good for Black, for example} 17. Ne3 (17. e5 Nd7 $17 (17... Nd5 $17 18. h3 Be6) 18. e6 Bxe6 19. Bxg6 Nc4 $17 ({or} 19... fxg6 20. Rxe6 Kf7 $17)) 17... Be6 $15) 15... Re8 $1 16. Ng3 Nc4 {Black has several good alternatives:} (16... Nd7 $15) (16... Bxf3 17. gxf3 (17. Qxf3 Nxd5 $17) 17... h5 $15) (16... Ra7 $5 $15) 17. h3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 (18. Qxf3 {is again met by} Nxd5 $17) 18... h5 ({Even better was} 18... Qa5 $1 $17 {, threatening Nxd5.}) 19. f4 h4 20. Nf1 Nh5 21. Rb1 Bh6 22. b3 Nb6 23. Qg4 Nxd5 24. f5 Bxc1 25. Rbxc1 Ndf4 26. e5 Rxe5 27. Rxe5 dxe5 28. fxg6 Qg5 29. Kh2 Qxg4 30. hxg4 Nf6 31. gxf7+ Kxf7 32. Bf5 Ne6 33. Ne3 Rd8 34. Bxe6+ Kxe6 35. Rxc5 Rd2 36. Rc6+ Kf7 37. g5 Rxf2+ 38. Kg1 Ne4 39. Ng4 Rxa2 40. Nxe5+ Ke7 41. Ng6+ Kd7 42. Ne5+ Kd8 43. Rh6 Nxg5 44. Rxh4 Re2 45. Nd3 Rd2 46. Rh8+ Kc7 47. Nc5 a5 48. Rh6 Rc2 49. Na6+ Kb7 50. b4 a4 51. Nc5+ Kc7 52. Ra6 Nf3+ 53. Kf1 Nd2+ 54. Ke1 Ra2 55. Ne6+ Kb7 56. Nc5+ Kc7 57. Ne6+ Kd7 58. Nd4 Nc4 59. Nxb5 a3 60. Nxa3 Nxa3 61. Kf1 Kc7 62. Kg1 Kb7 63. b5 Kc7 64. Kf1 Kb7 65. Kg1 Rb2 66. Rxa3 Rxb5 67. Kf2 1/2-1/2

