{[%evp 0,8,23,25,21,15,15,14,9,1,9] The last two lectures are dedicated to the main line in the Italian Game arising after} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 {On the diagram, we can see one of the most popular opening tabiyas nowadays. Countless top-level games featured this position. A typical feature for most of the lines in Italian Game are the complex move orders. The good news is that you are covered against all the subtleties related to move orders. The suggested system works against pretty much everything.  Regardless of what White does, our next moves will be ...a7-a6, ...d7-d6, and ...Ba7. In the first lecture about this system, Papaioannou explains the essential strategic concepts that one needs to know in order to handle these positions. The second lecture covers White's most challenging setups. As a matter of fact, you can play this system without the need to remember any concrete theory!} *

[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Common Mistakes by White"]
[Black "1) Premature Bg5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C54"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "20"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 {Both sides have many different moves that usually transpose to the same positions.} (5. Nbd2 $144) (5. O-O $144) 5... a6 (5... d6 $144) 6. O-O d6 (6... Ba7 $144) 7. Bb3 Ba7 8. Bg5 $2 {This move is usually premature if Black hasn't castled short yet.} (8. Re1 O-O 9. Bg5 $6 {This is another less common case of a badly timed Bg5: Relying on the Nxg5 sacrifice when f2 is unprotected.} h6 10. Bh4 (10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Rxe3 Nh5 $15) 10... g5 11. Nxg5 $2 ({It is not too late to play} 11. Bg3 {, when Black only has a slight advantage after} Nh7 {, followed by h6-h5.}) 11... hxg5 12. Bxg5 {White relies on the threat of Qf3, with a pin that is very difficult to shake off, but misses the simple reply} Bg4 $1 13. Bxf6 Bxf2+ $1 {Oops.} 14. Kf1 Bxd1 15. Bxd8 Bxe1 16. Bf6 Bxb3 17. axb3 Bxc3 18. Nxc3 Nb4 $19) 8... h6 9. Bh4 ({After} 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 $17 {, White has no compensation for Black's pair of bishops. Black's next moves will probably be 0-0, Ne7-g6, possibly with g7-g5 inserted.}) 9... g5 10. Bg3 Bg4 $15 {Black will castle long and obtain good attacking chances on the kingside.} (10... Ne7 $144) (10... Qe7 $144) *

[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Common Mistakes by White"]
[Black "2) Premature h2-h3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C54"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 {Both sides have many different moves that usually transpose to the same positions.} (5. Nbd2 $144) (5. O-O $144) 5... a6 (5... d6 $144) 6. O-O d6 (6... Ba7 $144) 7. Bb3 Ba7 8. h3 $6 {This is similar to the premature Bg5 in that it accelerates Black's kingside play.} h6 $1 {Once the black g-pawn arrives on g4, White is in serious trouble. That's why White has to play energetically now to stay in the game.} ({Also interesting is} 8... Rg8 $5 {, intending to play g7-g5 without the loss of a tempo in some lines but also foregoing the right to castle short.}) 9. Be3 ({Slow play is very dangerous now:} 9. Nbd2 g5 10. Nh2 (10. Nc4 g4 11. hxg4 Bxg4 12. Be3 Rg8 13. Bxa7 Rxa7) 10... g4 11. hxg4 Rg8 $40) (9. d4 {Immediately seeking counterplay in the centre also makes sense.} Qe7 10. dxe5 dxe5 {"What is the best way to take back on e5?" is a frequently asked question in the Italian without a clear answer that fits for every position. In this case, there should be no reason to exchange knights. The one on f3 can still be the target of g7-g5-g4 ideas while Black's queen's knight could prove useful later by harassing the b3-bishop:} 11. Qe2 O-O {A change of plans after White has announced his intention to play Be3.} (11... g5 $5 {is also playable.}) 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Na5 14. Bc2 Nc4 15. Qc1 b5 $15) 9... g5 10. Bxa7 Nxa7 11. d4 Qe7 12. Nbd2 g4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 $40 {Followed by Rg8 and (if White doesn't prevent it) 0-0-0. Black has good attacking chances on the kingside.} *

