[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "28"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 {Both sides have many different moves that usually transpose to the same positions.} (5. Nbd2 $144) (5. O-O $144) 5... a6 (5... d6 $144) 6. O-O d6 (6... Ba7 $144) 7. Bb3 (7. Nbd2 Ba7 8. Re1 $6 {This is another case of the move Re1 not being well timed.} O-O $1 $15 {This quiet and inconspicuous move creates two positional threats. White cannot defend against both Ng4 and Na5.} (8... Ng4 $6 9. Re2 {Black is in no position to play f7-f5 very soon, so the g4-knight will just be bounced back.}) (8... Na5 $6 {A good positional idea that also falls short with the king still in the centre:} 9. Bd5 $1 c6 (9... Nxd5 10. exd5 $16) 10. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 11. b4 $14 {Winning back the pawn with a favourable position, as Black's will have to spend some time securing his exposed king, taking the pawn on a5 and keeping the b7-pawn from becoming a target.})) 7... Ba7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Re1 $2 Ng4 $1 10. Rf1 (10. Re2 Kh8 $1 {leads to similar positions.}) 10... Kh8 $1 11. h3 f5 $1 (11... Nh6 $5 $15 {, preparing f7-f5, is usually a good alternative in these positions if Black prefers not to sacrifice.}) 12. exf5 ({After} 12. hxg4 $2 fxg4 13. Ne1 Qh4 {, Black wins back the material and keeps a strong kingside initiative.} 14. Ndf3 gxf3 15. Nxf3 Qh5 16. Nh2 Bxf2+) 12... Nh6 13. g4 Nxf5 14. gxf5 Bxf5 $40 {With two pawns and a strong attack for the sacrificed piece.} *

[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Common Mistakes by White"]
[Black "4) Premature d3-d4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C54"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 {Both sides have many different moves that usually transpose to the same positions.} (5. Nbd2 $144) (5. O-O $144) 5... a6 (5... d6 $144) 6. O-O d6 (6... Ba7 $144) 7. a4 (7. d4 $6 {Winning a tempo against the c5-bishop and trying to destabilise Black's uncastled position at the earliest possible moment. However, with the queenside and all major pieces still undeveloped, White is not ready for this yet.} Ba7 8. Re1 ({The greedy} 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bxf7 $2 {fails due to} Rf8 $17 12. Bc4 Nxe4 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. fxe3 Rxf1+ 15. Kxf1 Ke7 $17) 8... Bg4 $1 $36 9. Nbd2 $1 {is an unexpected resource that keeps White alive:} (9. dxe5 $2 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nxe5 11. Qe2 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 Ng4 $19) 9... O-O (9... exd4 10. e5 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5+ Kf8 $13) 10. h3 Bh5 11. d5 Ne7 $11 {With Black's bishop sidelined on h5, this structure is more acceptable for White, but still, Black should not have any particular problems.}) 7... Ba7 8. Re1 O-O 9. d4 $2 {This is even worse than two moves earlier, as Black is now perfectly positioned to attack White's centre:} exd4 $1 {It turns out that White is in no position to support his central pair of pawns.} ({The standard move} 9... Bg4 {is also good, as it forces White to accept a very unpleasant King's Indian type of position.} 10. d5 (10. dxe5 $2 Nxe5 11. Bb3 (11. Be2 Nxe4 $19) 11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nh5 $19 {Followed by Qh4. White's kingside collapses.}) 10... Ne7 $15 {, for example} 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Rxe3 h6 {, followed by Nh7 and f7-f5.} (12... a5 $6)) 10. Nxd4 (10. cxd4 Bg4 $17 {White either has to lose a central pawn right away or opt for the even worse} 11. d5 $6 Ne5 12. Bd3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Nh5 {, followed by Qh4, with a decisive advantage for Black.}) 10... Re8 $1 $17 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bg5 (12. Bd3 Ng4 $19) 12... h6 13. Bxf6 (13. Bh4 g5 {simply drops the e4-pawn.}) 13... Qxf6 $17 {With the bishop pair and the pressure and tactical threats on the dark squares, Black has a huge advantage.} *

