1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O a6 7. a4 Ba7 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3 Be6 {if you want to avoid the possiblity of 10.Bxe6-fe6 11.Be3 , (which is nothing special for white anyway) you can try 9...h6!? in this move order...waiting for 10.Nbd2 , and only now play Be6 .....its just a matter of taste!} 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. b4 ({Some White players delay Nbd2 in order to follow-up Bxe6 fxe6 with} 11. Be3 {, forcing the exchange of both bishops. The rook on e3 protects the f3-knight, which makes a later g2-g3 possible. This is a respectable idea, but nothing to worry about, for example} Bxe3 12. Rxe3 a5 $5 {Staking some claim on the queenside. Now d3-d4 can always be answered with e5xd4 c3xe4 Nb4. While this is fully acceptable for Black, it can also simply be avoided by playing 9...h6 first.} (12... Qe8 $5 13. Nbd2 Nh5 $132 {can still be considered.})) 11... Nh5 12. Ra2 Qe8 13. Na3 Nf4 14. Bxf4 Rxf4 15. Nc4 Qg6 16. b5 Raf8 $1 $15 17. Ncd2 Ne7 18. d4 Qf6 $1 19. dxe5 dxe5 20. bxa6 bxa6 21. Qe2 a5 22. Rf1 g5 $1 23. Nc4 Ng6 $1 24. Nh2 (24. Nxa5 $2 g4 25. hxg4 Rxg4 26. Ne1 Qg5 $19) 24... Qg7 25. Qd3 Nh4 26. Ng4 h5 27. Ngxe5 g4 28. hxg4 hxg4 29. Qg3 Qg5 30. Re2 Kg7 31. Nd3 R4f6 32. Qxc7+ R8f7 33. Qe5 Qh6 34. Qg3 Kh8 $19 35. Rb2 Nf3+ 36. gxf3 gxf3 37. Rfb1 Rg7 38. Qxg7+ Qxg7+ 39. Kf1 Rh6 40. Ke1 Qxc3+ 0-1

