1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 a6 6. h3 d6 7. a4 Ba7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. O-O h6 $5 (9... Be6 $5 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Qb3 $6 {This is hardly ever a good move in the Italian. The queen is generally misplaced on b3 and will have to lose more time returning to better squares.} Qd7 12. Ng5 (12. Qxb7 $4 Rfb8 13. Qxa6 Bxf2+ $19) 12... d5 $1 $15 ({Even the simple} 12... Nd8 $1 $15 {is good enough.})) (9... Ne7 $5 {The plan of relocating the c6-knight to g6 is generally playable but not the author's first choice, unless White has already played b2-b4, in which case Ne7 prevents a tempo-winning b4-b5.} 10. d4 $6 {As often in the Italian (see part 1 of this Bc5 lecture), White should not play this move before his pieces are able to support the centre.} ({The correct path is} 10. Re1 $1 Ng6 11. Nf1 {, with reasonable chances to play for an advantage.}) 10... Nc6 $1 {It is counter-intuitive to immediately move back a piece to where it came from, but the situation has changed: After White's premature advance, Black should apply pressure on the centre immediately, and for this purpose, c6 is a better square than g6. In fact, White is already unable to keep the tension.} ({The standard response} 10... exd4 11. cxd4 d5 {falls short due to} 12. e5 $1 dxc4 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Nxc4 {Black's light-squared bishop is very strong but cannot compensate for the permanent weakening of his king's position.}) {A possible line is} 11. dxe5 (11. d5 $2 Ne7 $15 {A King's Indian type of position with a black bishop on the g1-a7 diagonal is rarely desirable for White. For example} 12. Re1 h6 13. a5 Nh7 {, preparing f7-f5.}) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 {Now the position is equal, but it's already White who needs to tread more carefully.} 13. Qe2 Qe7 14. Nf3 a5 (14... h6 $5) 15. Be3 $6 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Bd7 $15) 10. Re1 Be6 $1 11. Bxe6 (11. Nf1 $2 Bxc4 $15 {Generally the correct move if White offers the capture on c4.} ({In this particular position, even stronger is} 11... Nxe4 $1 12. Rxe4 d5 $17) 12. dxc4 {White now has strong control over the d5-square, but his pawns have become less flexible and Black should build on that with} a5 $1 {, preventing a4-a5. A possible line is} 13. Ng3 Kh7 14. Nf5 Ne7 $1 {, threatening Nxe4 and ejecting White's strong knight.}) 11... fxe6 {These pawns may be a liability in an endgame, but for now, there is a middlegame with an opened f-file and a bishop on the a7-g1 diagonal ahead.} 12. Nf1 (12. b4 {Now Black can play the standard knight manoeuvre immediately or first transfer the queen to the kingside:} Nh5 (12... Qe8 13. Ra2 Nh5 $132 (13... Qg6 $144 $132) (13... Ne7 $144 $132) 14. Nf1 {It is important to keep in mind that after for example} Ne7 15. d4 (15. Be3 Nf4 16. Bxf4 Rxf4 $132) 15... exd4 16. cxd4 {, the position in the centre has changed and the knight should go back to what has suddenly become a fantastic square.} Nc6 17. Rb2 e5 $36) 13. Ra2 {Overprotecting f2 makes sense in many lines, but the main idea is to play b4-b5 later without losing the rook to a6xb5 a4xb5 Bxf2+.} Qf6 14. Nc4 Nf4 (14... Ne7 $132) 15. Bxf4 Qxf4 16. b5 Ne7 $132) 12... Nh5 $1 {White cannot keep the knight out of f4 without major concessions:} 13. Be3 (13. g3 $6 {White would like to control f4 like this, but now the light squares are weakened, which is very relevant for the protection of the f-file's defender, the f3-knight.} Qf6 14. Kg2 Qg6 (14... Qxf3+ $5 15. Qxf3 Rxf3 16. Kxf3 Rf8+ 17. Kg2 Rxf2+ 18. Kh1 Ne7 $44) 15. Be3 (15. Ne3 $2 Nf4+ 16. Kh2 Nxd3 $19) 15... Nf4+ 16. Bxf4 Rxf4 $36) (13. b4 Nf4 (13... Qf6 $5) 14. Bxf4 Rxf4 $36) 13... Nf4 $1 14. d4 $2 (14. Bxa7 Nxa7 $1 {The correct recapture, freeing the c-pawn for a possible c7-c5.} 15. Ng3 (15. Ne3 c5 $132) (15. b4 Qf6 $36 16. N1h2 Qg6 $17) 15... c5 $1 16. Re3 {This overprotects f3, but thanks to Black's last move, the rook can become a target after} (16. d4 $2 exd4 17. cxd4 Nc6 $1 {The point.} 18. dxc5 (18. d5 exd5 19. exd5 Nb4 $17 {is a great Benoni type position for Black.}) 18... dxc5 $17 {, for example} 19. Qxd8 Rfxd8 20. Re3 b5 21. Rc1 c4 $17) 16... Nc6 $36 {, followed by d6-d5-d4.}) (14. Ng3 $6 Qf6 15. Kh2 Ne7 {Bringing another piece into the attack and preparing the following sacrifice:} (15... Rf7 $5) 16. b4 Neg6 17. Ra2 $2 ({It was necessary to overprotect the knight with} 17. Bxa7 Rxa7 18. Re3) 17... Nxg2 $1 18. Kxg2 Qxf3+ $19) 14... Qf6 $17 ({Also good was} 14... exd4 $5 15. cxd4 Qf6 16. N1h2 Qg6 17. Bxf4 Rxf4 $17) 15. Kh2 (15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 $17) 15... Rf7 (15... exd4 $1 16. cxd4 Nb4 $15 {may have been even better.}) 16. Ng3 Raf8 (16... exd4 $5 17. cxd4 Raf8) 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Bxa7 Nxa7 19. Re3 Nc8 20. b4 Ne7 21. b5 a5 22. c4 g5 23. Raa3 Neg6 24. Ne1 Nh4 (24... Rd8 $1 25. Qc2 h5 $17) 25. Ra2 Rh7 26. Rd2 h5 27. Nh1 g4 28. g3 Nxh3 29. gxh4 Qxh4 30. Ng2 Qg5 31. Rd7 Rff7 32. Rxf7 Rxf7 33. Qd2 h4 34. Qe2 Nf4 35. Qd1 g3+ 36. fxg3 Nxg2 37. Rd3 Ne3 38. Qe2 hxg3+ 39. Nxg3 Rh7+ 0-1

