1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 a6 6. O-O d6 7. Bb3 Ba7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. h3 Be6 (9... h6 $144 10. Re1 Be6) (9... Ne7 $5) 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. b4 (11. Nc4 b5 (11... Qe8 12. b4 $2 d5 $17)) (11. Re1 Nh5 $1 12. Nf1 Qe8 $1 $36 (12... h6 {transposes to Abdussatorov's game, but by choosing this move order, Black tries to avoid losing time with this pawn move.}) 13. Be3 Nf4 14. Bxa7 Nxa7 $1 $15 15. Re3 (15. Ng3 $2 Qb5) (15. b4 $6 Qg6 16. Ng3 Rf7 $17) 15... c5 $1 16. Ng3 Qg6 $36) 11... Qe8 $1 ({Also good was} 11... Nh5 12. Nc4 Nf4 13. Bxf4 Rxf4 14. Ncd2 Ne7 15. a4 Qd7 16. g3 Rf6 17. Kg2 Raf8 18. b5 axb5 19. axb5 Bb6 $36) 12. Nc4 $2 (12. a4 Nh5 $1 13. Nc4 $2 d5 $1 $17 {This is an important idea to keep in mind when playing this type of position with Qe8.} 14. Ncxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Ng3 $17) 12... Nh5 $6 ({Better was} 12... d5 $1 $17 13. Ncxe5 $2 dxe4 14. dxe4 Nxe4 $17 15. Qc2 Nxf2 16. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 17. Qxf2 Nxe5 $19) 13. a4 Ne7 14. Be3 Nf4 $1 {It was possible to play this earlier, but Black waited for White to play Be3 in order to slightly discourage her opponent from playing Bxf4.} 15. Bxa7 Rxa7 16. g3 Nh5 17. Ng5 Rf6 18. Ne3 Qg6 19. h4 h6 20. Nf3 Ra8 21. Nh2 Raf8 22. Neg4 R6f7 23. Qe2 Kh8 24. b5 a5 25. d4 exd4 26. cxd4 Ng8 27. Ra3 Ngf6 28. Re3 Nd7 29. Kh1 Nb6 30. Qd1 Nf6 31. Nxf6 Rxf6 32. Qg4 Qf7 33. f4 e5 34. dxe5 dxe5 35. f5 Rd6 36. Nf3 Qf6 37. Rc1 Rf7 38. Rec3 Rdd7 39. Qh5 Rfe7 40. g4 Qd6 41. g5 Nxa4 42. f6 Rf7 43. Rc4 Nb2 44. fxg7+ Rxg7 45. Rc5 Nd3 46. Rd5 Qe6 0-1

